\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: VOLTIMAND
\LINE: Most fair return of greetings and desires.
\LINE: Upon our first, he sent out to suppress
\LINE: His nephew's levies; which to him appear'd
\LINE: To be a preparation 'gainst the Polack;
\LINE: But, better look'd into, he truly found
\LINE: It was against your highness: whereat grieved,
\LINE: That so his sickness, age and impotence
\LINE: Was falsely borne in hand, sends out arrests
\LINE: On Fortinbras; which he, in brief, obeys;
\LINE: Receives rebuke from Norway, and in fine
\LINE: Makes vow before his uncle never more
\LINE: To give the assay of arms against your majesty.
\LINE: Whereon old Norway, overcome with joy,
\LINE: Gives him three thousand crowns in annual fee,
\LINE: And his commission to employ those soldiers,
\LINE: So levied as before, against the Polack:
\LINE: With an entreaty, herein further shown,
\STAGEDIR: Giving a paper
\LINE: That it might please you to give quiet pass
\LINE: Through your dominions for this enterprise,
\LINE: On such regards of safety and allowance
\LINE: As therein are set down.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: It likes us well;
\LINE: And at our more consider'd time well read,
\LINE: Answer, and think upon this business.
\LINE: Meantime we thank you for your well-took labour:
\LINE: Go to your rest; at night we'll feast together:
\LINE: Most welcome home!
>


\STAGEDIR: Exeunt VOLTIMAND and CORNELIUS

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: This business is well ended.
\LINE: My liege, and madam, to expostulate
\LINE: What majesty should be, what duty is,
\LINE: Why day is day, night night, and time is time,
\LINE: Were nothing but to waste night, day and time.
\LINE: Therefore, since brevity is the soul of wit,
\LINE: And tediousness the limbs and outward flourishes,
\LINE: I will be brief: your noble son is mad:
\LINE: Mad call I it; for, to define true madness,
\LINE: What is't but to be nothing else but mad?
\LINE: But let that go.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: More matter, with less art.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: Madam, I swear I use no art at all.
\LINE: That he is mad, 'tis true: 'tis true 'tis pity;
\LINE: And pity 'tis 'tis true: a foolish figure;
\LINE: But farewell it, for I will use no art.
\LINE: Mad let us grant him, then: and now remains
\LINE: That we find out the cause of this effect,
\LINE: Or rather say, the cause of this defect,
\LINE: For this effect defective comes by cause:
\LINE: Thus it remains, and the remainder thus. Perpend.
\LINE: I have a daughter--have while she is mine--
\LINE: Who, in her duty and obedience, mark,
\LINE: Hath given me this: now gather, and surmise.
\STAGEDIR: Reads
\LINE: 'To the celestial and my soul's idol, the most
\LINE: beautified Ophelia,'--
\LINE: That's an ill phrase, a vile phrase; 'beautified' is
\LINE: a vile phrase: but you shall hear. Thus:
\STAGEDIR: Reads
\LINE: 'In her excellent white bosom, these, &amp;c.'
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Came this from Hamlet to her?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: Good madam, stay awhile; I will be faithful.
\STAGEDIR: Reads
\LINE: 'Doubt thou the stars are fire;
\LINE: Doubt that the sun doth move;
\LINE: Doubt truth to be a liar;
\LINE: But never doubt I love.
\LINE: 'O dear Ophelia, I am ill at these numbers;
\LINE: I have not art to reckon my groans: but that
\LINE: I love thee best, O most best, believe it. Adieu.
\LINE: 'Thine evermore most dear lady, whilst
\LINE: this machine is to him, HAMLET.'
\LINE: This, in obedience, hath my daughter shown me,
\LINE: And more above, hath his solicitings,
\LINE: As they fell out by time, by means and place,
\LINE: All given to mine ear.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: But how hath she
\LINE: Received his love?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: What do you think of me?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: As of a man faithful and honourable.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: I would fain prove so. But what might you think,
\LINE: When I had seen this hot love on the wing--
\LINE: As I perceived it, I must tell you that,
\LINE: Before my daughter told me--what might you,
\LINE: Or my dear majesty your queen here, think,
\LINE: If I had play'd the desk or table-book,
\LINE: Or given my heart a winking, mute and dumb,
\LINE: Or look'd upon this love with idle sight;
\LINE: What might you think? No, I went round to work,
\LINE: And my young mistress thus I did bespeak:
\LINE: 'Lord Hamlet is a prince, out of thy star;
\LINE: This must not be:' and then I precepts gave her,
\LINE: That she should lock herself from his resort,
\LINE: Admit no messengers, receive no tokens.
\LINE: Which done, she took the fruits of my advice;
\LINE: And he, repulsed--a short tale to make--
\LINE: Fell into a sadness, then into a fast,
\LINE: Thence to a watch, thence into a weakness,
\LINE: Thence to a lightness, and, by this declension,
\LINE: Into the madness wherein now he raves,
\LINE: And all we mourn for.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Do you think 'tis this?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: It may be, very likely.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: Hath there been such a time--I'd fain know that--
\LINE: That I have positively said 'Tis so,'
\LINE: When it proved otherwise?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Not that I know.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Pointing to his head and shoulder>>
\LINE: Take this from this, if this be otherwise:
\LINE: If circumstances lead me, I will find
\LINE: Where truth is hid, though it were hid indeed
\LINE: Within the centre.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: How may we try it further?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: You know, sometimes he walks four hours together
\LINE: Here in the lobby.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: So he does indeed.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: At such a time I'll loose my daughter to him:
\LINE: Be you and I behind an arras then;
\LINE: Mark the encounter: if he love her not
\LINE: And be not from his reason fall'n thereon,
\LINE: Let me be no assistant for a state,
\LINE: But keep a farm and carters.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: We will try it.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: But, look, where sadly the poor wretch comes reading.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: Away, I do beseech you, both away:
\LINE: I'll board him presently.
\STAGEDIR<Exeunt KING CLAUDIUS, QUEEN GERTRUDE, and
Attendants>
\STAGEDIR: Enter HAMLET, reading
\LINE: O, give me leave:
\LINE: How does my good Lord Hamlet?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Well, God-a-mercy.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: Do you know me, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Excellent well; you are a fishmonger.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: Not I, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Then I would you were so honest a man.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: Honest, my lord!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Ay, sir; to be honest, as this world goes, is to be
\LINE: one man picked out of ten thousand.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: That's very true, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: For if the sun breed maggots in a dead dog, being a
\LINE: god kissing carrion,--Have you a daughter?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: I have, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Let her not walk i' the sun: conception is a
\LINE: blessing: but not as your daughter may conceive.
\LINE: Friend, look to 't.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Aside>  How say you by that? Still harping on my>
\LINE: daughter: yet he knew me not at first; he said I
\LINE: was a fishmonger: he is far gone, far gone: and
\LINE: truly in my youth I suffered much extremity for
\LINE: love; very near this. I'll speak to him again.
\LINE: What do you read, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Words, words, words.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: What is the matter, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Between who?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: I mean, the matter that you read, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Slanders, sir: for the satirical rogue says here
\LINE: that old men have grey beards, that their faces are
\LINE: wrinkled, their eyes purging thick amber and
\LINE: plum-tree gum and that they have a plentiful lack of
\LINE: wit, together with most weak hams: all which, sir,
\LINE: though I most powerfully and potently believe, yet
\LINE: I hold it not honesty to have it thus set down, for
\LINE: yourself, sir, should be old as I am, if like a crab
\LINE: you could go backward.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Aside>  Though this be madness, yet there is method>
\LINE: in 't. Will you walk out of the air, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Into my grave.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: Indeed, that is out o' the air.
\STAGEDIR: Aside
\LINE: How pregnant sometimes his replies are! a happiness
\LINE: that often madness hits on, which reason and sanity
\LINE: could not so prosperously be delivered of. I will
\LINE: leave him, and suddenly contrive the means of
\LINE: meeting between him and my daughter.--My honourable
\LINE: lord, I will most humbly take my leave of you.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: You cannot, sir, take from me any thing that I will
\LINE: more willingly part withal: except my life, except
\LINE: my life, except my life.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: Fare you well, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: These tedious old fools!
>


\STAGEDIR: Enter ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: You go to seek the Lord Hamlet; there he is.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<To POLONIUS>  God save you, sir!>
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit POLONIUS

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: My honoured lord!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: My most dear lord!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: My excellent good friends! How dost thou,
\LINE: Guildenstern? Ah, Rosencrantz! Good lads, how do ye both?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: As the indifferent children of the earth.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: Happy, in that we are not over-happy;
\LINE: On fortune's cap we are not the very button.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Nor the soles of her shoe?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Neither, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Then you live about her waist, or in the middle of
\LINE: her favours?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: 'Faith, her privates we.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: In the secret parts of fortune? O, most true; she
\LINE: is a strumpet. What's the news?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: None, my lord, but that the world's grown honest.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Then is doomsday near: but your news is not true.
\LINE: Let me question more in particular: what have you,
\LINE: my good friends, deserved at the hands of fortune,
\LINE: that she sends you to prison hither?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: Prison, my lord!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Denmark's a prison.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Then is the world one.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: A goodly one; in which there are many confines,
\LINE: wards and dungeons, Denmark being one o' the worst.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: We think not so, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Why, then, 'tis none to you; for there is nothing
\LINE: either good or bad, but thinking makes it so: to me
\LINE: it is a prison.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Why then, your ambition makes it one; 'tis too
\LINE: narrow for your mind.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: O God, I could be bounded in a nut shell and count
\LINE: myself a king of infinite space, were it not that I
\LINE: have bad dreams.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: Which dreams indeed are ambition, for the very
\LINE: substance of the ambitious is merely the shadow of a dream.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: A dream itself is but a shadow.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Truly, and I hold ambition of so airy and light a
\LINE: quality that it is but a shadow's shadow.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Then are our beggars bodies, and our monarchs and
\LINE: outstretched heroes the beggars' shadows. Shall we
\LINE: to the court? for, by my fay, I cannot reason.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: We'll wait upon you.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: No such matter: I will not sort you with the rest
\LINE: of my servants, for, to speak to you like an honest
\LINE: man, I am most dreadfully attended. But, in the
\LINE: beaten way of friendship, what make you at Elsinore?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: To visit you, my lord; no other occasion.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Beggar that I am, I am even poor in thanks; but I
\LINE: thank you: and sure, dear friends, my thanks are
\LINE: too dear a halfpenny. Were you not sent for? Is it
\LINE: your own inclining? Is it a free visitation? Come,
\LINE: deal justly with me: come, come; nay, speak.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: What should we say, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Why, any thing, but to the purpose. You were sent
\LINE: for; and there is a kind of confession in your looks
\LINE: which your modesties have not craft enough to colour:
\LINE: I know the good king and queen have sent for you.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: To what end, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: That you must teach me. But let me conjure you, by
\LINE: the rights of our fellowship, by the consonancy of
\LINE: our youth, by the obligation of our ever-preserved
\LINE: love, and by what more dear a better proposer could
\LINE: charge you withal, be even and direct with me,
\LINE: whether you were sent for, or no?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Aside to GUILDENSTERN>  What say you?>
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Aside>  Nay, then, I have an eye of you.--If you>
\LINE: love me, hold not off.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: My lord, we were sent for.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I will tell you why; so shall my anticipation
\LINE: prevent your discovery, and your secrecy to the king
\LINE: and queen moult no feather. I have of late--but
\LINE: wherefore I know not--lost all my mirth, forgone all
\LINE: custom of exercises; and indeed it goes so heavily
\LINE: with my disposition that this goodly frame, the
\LINE: earth, seems to me a sterile promontory, this most
\LINE: excellent canopy, the air, look you, this brave
\LINE: o'erhanging firmament, this majestical roof fretted
\LINE: with golden fire, why, it appears no other thing to
\LINE: me than a foul and pestilent congregation of vapours.
\LINE: What a piece of work is a man! how noble in reason!
\LINE: how infinite in faculty! in form and moving how
\LINE: express and admirable! in action how like an angel!
\LINE: in apprehension how like a god! the beauty of the
\LINE: world! the paragon of animals! And yet, to me,
\LINE: what is this quintessence of dust? man delights not
\LINE: me: no, nor woman neither, though by your smiling
\LINE: you seem to say so.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: My lord, there was no such stuff in my thoughts.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Why did you laugh then, when I said 'man delights not me'?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: To think, my lord, if you delight not in man, what
\LINE: lenten entertainment the players shall receive from
\LINE: you: we coted them on the way; and hither are they
\LINE: coming, to offer you service.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: He that plays the king shall be welcome; his majesty
\LINE: shall have tribute of me; the adventurous knight
\LINE: shall use his foil and target; the lover shall not
\LINE: sigh gratis; the humourous man shall end his part
\LINE: in peace; the clown shall make those laugh whose
\LINE: lungs are tickled o' the sere; and the lady shall
\LINE: say her mind freely, or the blank verse shall halt
\LINE: for't. What players are they?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Even those you were wont to take delight in, the
\LINE: tragedians of the city.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: How chances it they travel? their residence, both
\LINE: in reputation and profit, was better both ways.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: I think their inhibition comes by the means of the
\LINE: late innovation.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Do they hold the same estimation they did when I was
\LINE: in the city? are they so followed?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: No, indeed, are they not.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: How comes it? do they grow rusty?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Nay, their endeavour keeps in the wonted pace: but
\LINE: there is, sir, an aery of children, little eyases,
\LINE: that cry out on the top of question, and are most
\LINE: tyrannically clapped for't: these are now the
\LINE: fashion, and so berattle the common stages--so they
\LINE: call them--that many wearing rapiers are afraid of
\LINE: goose-quills and dare scarce come thither.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: What, are they children? who maintains 'em? how are
\LINE: they escoted? Will they pursue the quality no
\LINE: longer than they can sing? will they not say
\LINE: afterwards, if they should grow themselves to common
\LINE: players--as it is most like, if their means are no
\LINE: better--their writers do them wrong, to make them
\LINE: exclaim against their own succession?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: 'Faith, there has been much to do on both sides; and
\LINE: the nation holds it no sin to tarre them to
\LINE: controversy: there was, for a while, no money bid
\LINE: for argument, unless the poet and the player went to
\LINE: cuffs in the question.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Is't possible?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: O, there has been much throwing about of brains.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Do the boys carry it away?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Ay, that they do, my lord; Hercules and his load too.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: It is not very strange; for mine uncle is king of
\LINE: Denmark, and those that would make mows at him while
\LINE: my father lived, give twenty, forty, fifty, an
\LINE: hundred ducats a-piece for his picture in little.
\LINE: 'Sblood, there is something in this more than
\LINE: natural, if philosophy could find it out.
>


\STAGEDIR: Flourish of trumpets within

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: There are the players.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Gentlemen, you are welcome to Elsinore. Your hands,
\LINE: come then: the appurtenance of welcome is fashion
\LINE: and ceremony: let me comply with you in this garb,
\LINE: lest my extent to the players, which, I tell you,
\LINE: must show fairly outward, should more appear like
\LINE: entertainment than yours. You are welcome: but my
\LINE: uncle-father and aunt-mother are deceived.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: In what, my dear lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I am but mad north-north-west: when the wind is
\LINE: southerly I know a hawk from a handsaw.
>


\STAGEDIR: Enter POLONIUS

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: Well be with you, gentlemen!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Hark you, Guildenstern; and you too: at each ear a
\LINE: hearer: that great baby you see there is not yet
\LINE: out of his swaddling-clouts.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Happily he's the second time come to them; for they
\LINE: say an old man is twice a child.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I will prophesy he comes to tell me of the players;
\LINE: mark it. You say right, sir: o' Monday morning;
\LINE: 'twas so indeed.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: My lord, I have news to tell you.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: My lord, I have news to tell you.
\LINE: When Roscius was an actor in Rome,--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: The actors are come hither, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Buz, buz!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: Upon mine honour,--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Then came each actor on his ass,--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: The best actors in the world, either for tragedy,
\LINE: comedy, history, pastoral, pastoral-comical,
\LINE: historical-pastoral, tragical-historical, tragical-
\LINE: comical-historical-pastoral, scene individable, or
\LINE: poem unlimited: Seneca cannot be too heavy, nor
\LINE: Plautus too light. For the law of writ and the
\LINE: liberty, these are the only men.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: O Jephthah, judge of Israel, what a treasure hadst thou!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: What a treasure had he, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Why,
\LINE: 'One fair daughter and no more,
\LINE: The which he loved passing well.'
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Aside>  Still on my daughter.>
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Am I not i' the right, old Jephthah?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: If you call me Jephthah, my lord, I have a daughter
\LINE: that I love passing well.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Nay, that follows not.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: What follows, then, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Why,
\LINE: 'As by lot, God wot,'
\LINE: and then, you know,
\LINE: 'It came to pass, as most like it was,'--
\LINE: the first row of the pious chanson will show you
\LINE: more; for look, where my abridgement comes.
\STAGEDIR: Enter four or five Players
\LINE: You are welcome, masters; welcome, all. I am glad
\LINE: to see thee well. Welcome, good friends. O, my old
\LINE: friend! thy face is valenced since I saw thee last:
\LINE: comest thou to beard me in Denmark? What, my young
\LINE: lady and mistress! By'r lady, your ladyship is
\LINE: nearer to heaven than when I saw you last, by the
\LINE: altitude of a chopine. Pray God, your voice, like
\LINE: apiece of uncurrent gold, be not cracked within the
\LINE: ring. Masters, you are all welcome. We'll e'en
\LINE: to't like French falconers, fly at any thing we see:
\LINE: we'll have a speech straight: come, give us a taste
\LINE: of your quality; come, a passionate speech.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Player
\LINE: What speech, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I heard thee speak me a speech once, but it was
\LINE: never acted; or, if it was, not above once; for the
\LINE: play, I remember, pleased not the million; 'twas
\LINE: caviare to the general: but it was--as I received
\LINE: it, and others, whose judgments in such matters
\LINE: cried in the top of mine--an excellent play, well
\LINE: digested in the scenes, set down with as much
\LINE: modesty as cunning. I remember, one said there
\LINE: were no sallets in the lines to make the matter
\LINE: savoury, nor no matter in the phrase that might
\LINE: indict the author of affectation; but called it an
\LINE: honest method, as wholesome as sweet, and by very
\LINE: much more handsome than fine. One speech in it I
\LINE: chiefly loved: 'twas Aeneas' tale to Dido; and
\LINE: thereabout of it especially, where he speaks of
\LINE: Priam's slaughter: if it live in your memory, begin
\LINE: at this line: let me see, let me see--
\LINE: 'The rugged Pyrrhus, like the Hyrcanian beast,'--
\LINE: it is not so:--it begins with Pyrrhus:--
\LINE: 'The rugged Pyrrhus, he whose sable arms,
\LINE: Black as his purpose, did the night resemble
\LINE: When he lay couched in the ominous horse,
\LINE: Hath now this dread and black complexion smear'd
\LINE: With heraldry more dismal; head to foot
\LINE: Now is he total gules; horridly trick'd
\LINE: With blood of fathers, mothers, daughters, sons,
\LINE: Baked and impasted with the parching streets,
\LINE: That lend a tyrannous and damned light
\LINE: To their lord's murder: roasted in wrath and fire,
\LINE: And thus o'er-sized with coagulate gore,
\LINE: With eyes like carbuncles, the hellish Pyrrhus
\LINE: Old grandsire Priam seeks.'
\LINE: So, proceed you.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: 'Fore God, my lord, well spoken, with good accent and
\LINE: good discretion.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Player
\LINE: 'Anon he finds him
\LINE: Striking too short at Greeks; his antique sword,
\LINE: Rebellious to his arm, lies where it falls,
\LINE: Repugnant to command: unequal match'd,
\LINE: Pyrrhus at Priam drives; in rage strikes wide;
\LINE: But with the whiff and wind of his fell sword
\LINE: The unnerved father falls. Then senseless Ilium,
\LINE: Seeming to feel this blow, with flaming top
\LINE: Stoops to his base, and with a hideous crash
\LINE: Takes prisoner Pyrrhus' ear: for, lo! his sword,
\LINE: Which was declining on the milky head
\LINE: Of reverend Priam, seem'd i' the air to stick:
\LINE: So, as a painted tyrant, Pyrrhus stood,
\LINE: And like a neutral to his will and matter,
\LINE: Did nothing.
\LINE: But, as we often see, against some storm,
\LINE: A silence in the heavens, the rack stand still,
\LINE: The bold winds speechless and the orb below
\LINE: As hush as death, anon the dreadful thunder
\LINE: Doth rend the region, so, after Pyrrhus' pause,
\LINE: Aroused vengeance sets him new a-work;
\LINE: And never did the Cyclops' hammers fall
\LINE: On Mars's armour forged for proof eterne
\LINE: With less remorse than Pyrrhus' bleeding sword
\LINE: Now falls on Priam.
\LINE: Out, out, thou strumpet, Fortune! All you gods,
\LINE: In general synod 'take away her power;
\LINE: Break all the spokes and fellies from her wheel,
\LINE: And bowl the round nave down the hill of heaven,
\LINE: As low as to the fiends!'
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: This is too long.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: It shall to the barber's, with your beard. Prithee,
\LINE: say on: he's for a jig or a tale of bawdry, or he
\LINE: sleeps: say on: come to Hecuba.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Player
\LINE: 'But who, O, who had seen the mobled queen--'
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: 'The mobled queen?'
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: That's good; 'mobled queen' is good.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Player
\LINE: 'Run barefoot up and down, threatening the flames
\LINE: With bisson rheum; a clout upon that head
\LINE: Where late the diadem stood, and for a robe,
\LINE: About her lank and all o'er-teemed loins,
\LINE: A blanket, in the alarm of fear caught up;
\LINE: Who this had seen, with tongue in venom steep'd,
\LINE: 'Gainst Fortune's state would treason have
\LINE: pronounced:
\LINE: But if the gods themselves did see her then
\LINE: When she saw Pyrrhus make malicious sport
\LINE: In mincing with his sword her husband's limbs,
\LINE: The instant burst of clamour that she made,
\LINE: Unless things mortal move them not at all,
\LINE: Would have made milch the burning eyes of heaven,
\LINE: And passion in the gods.'
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: Look, whether he has not turned his colour and has
\LINE: tears in's eyes. Pray you, no more.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: 'Tis well: I'll have thee speak out the rest soon.
\LINE: Good my lord, will you see the players well
\LINE: bestowed? Do you hear, let them be well used; for
\LINE: they are the abstract and brief chronicles of the
\LINE: time: after your death you were better have a bad
\LINE: epitaph than their ill report while you live.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: My lord, I will use them according to their desert.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: God's bodykins, man, much better: use every man
\LINE: after his desert, and who should 'scape whipping?
\LINE: Use them after your own honour and dignity: the less
\LINE: they deserve, the more merit is in your bounty.
\LINE: Take them in.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: Come, sirs.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Follow him, friends: we'll hear a play to-morrow.
\STAGEDIR: Exit POLONIUS with all the Players but the First
\LINE: Dost thou hear me, old friend; can you play the
\LINE: Murder of Gonzago?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Player
\LINE: Ay, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: We'll ha't to-morrow night. You could, for a need,
\LINE: study a speech of some dozen or sixteen lines, which
\LINE: I would set down and insert in't, could you not?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Player
\LINE: Ay, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Very well. Follow that lord; and look you mock him
\LINE: not.
\STAGEDIR: Exit First Player
\LINE: My good friends, I'll leave you till night: you are
\LINE: welcome to Elsinore.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Good my lord!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Ay, so, God be wi' ye;
\STAGEDIR: Exeunt ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: Now I am alone.
\LINE: O, what a rogue and peasant slave am I!
\LINE: Is it not monstrous that this player here,
\LINE: But in a fiction, in a dream of passion,
\LINE: Could force his soul so to his own conceit
\LINE: That from her working all his visage wann'd,
\LINE: Tears in his eyes, distraction in's aspect,
\LINE: A broken voice, and his whole function suiting
\LINE: With forms to his conceit? and all for nothing!
\LINE: For Hecuba!
\LINE: What's Hecuba to him, or he to Hecuba,
\LINE: That he should weep for her? What would he do,
\LINE: Had he the motive and the cue for passion
\LINE: That I have? He would drown the stage with tears
\LINE: And cleave the general ear with horrid speech,
\LINE: Make mad the guilty and appal the free,
\LINE: Confound the ignorant, and amaze indeed
\LINE: The very faculties of eyes and ears. Yet I,
\LINE: A dull and muddy-mettled rascal, peak,
\LINE: Like John-a-dreams, unpregnant of my cause,
\LINE: And can say nothing; no, not for a king,
\LINE: Upon whose property and most dear life
\LINE: A damn'd defeat was made. Am I a coward?
\LINE: Who calls me villain? breaks my pate across?
\LINE: Plucks off my beard, and blows it in my face?
\LINE: Tweaks me by the nose? gives me the lie i' the throat,
\LINE: As deep as to the lungs? who does me this?
\LINE: Ha!
\LINE: 'Swounds, I should take it: for it cannot be
\LINE: But I am pigeon-liver'd and lack gall
\LINE: To make oppression bitter, or ere this
\LINE: I should have fatted all the region kites
\LINE: With this slave's offal: bloody, bawdy villain!
\LINE: Remorseless, treacherous, lecherous, kindless villain!
\LINE: O, vengeance!
\LINE: Why, what an ass am I! This is most brave,
\LINE: That I, the son of a dear father murder'd,
\LINE: Prompted to my revenge by heaven and hell,
\LINE: Must, like a whore, unpack my heart with words,
\LINE: And fall a-cursing, like a very drab,
\LINE: A scullion!
\LINE: Fie upon't! foh! About, my brain! I have heard
\LINE: That guilty creatures sitting at a play
\LINE: Have by the very cunning of the scene
\LINE: Been struck so to the soul that presently
\LINE: They have proclaim'd their malefactions;
\LINE: For murder, though it have no tongue, will speak
\LINE: With most miraculous organ. I'll have these players
\LINE: Play something like the murder of my father
\LINE: Before mine uncle: I'll observe his looks;
\LINE: I'll tent him to the quick: if he but blench,
\LINE: I know my course. The spirit that I have seen
\LINE: May be the devil: and the devil hath power
\LINE: To assume a pleasing shape; yea, and perhaps
\LINE: Out of my weakness and my melancholy,
\LINE: As he is very potent with such spirits,
\LINE: Abuses me to damn me: I'll have grounds
\LINE: More relative than this: the play 's the thing
\LINE: Wherein I'll catch the conscience of the king.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit
>

>

\ACT<\TITLE: ACT III

\SCENE<\TITLE: SCENE I.  A room in the castle.
\STAGEDIR<Enter KING CLAUDIUS, QUEEN GERTRUDE, POLONIUS,
OPHELIA, ROSENCRANTZ, and GUILDENSTERN>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: And can you, by no drift of circumstance,
\LINE: Get from him why he puts on this confusion,
\LINE: Grating so harshly all his days of quiet
\LINE: With turbulent and dangerous lunacy?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: He does confess he feels himself distracted;
\LINE: But from what cause he will by no means speak.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: Nor do we find him forward to be sounded,
\LINE: But, with a crafty madness, keeps aloof,
\LINE: When we would bring him on to some confession
\LINE: Of his true state.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Did he receive you well?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Most like a gentleman.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: But with much forcing of his disposition.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Niggard of question; but, of our demands,
\LINE: Most free in his reply.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Did you assay him?
\LINE: To any pastime?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Madam, it so fell out, that certain players
\LINE: We o'er-raught on the way: of these we told him;
\LINE: And there did seem in him a kind of joy
\LINE: To hear of it: they are about the court,
\LINE: And, as I think, they have already order
\LINE: This night to play before him.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: 'Tis most true:
\LINE: And he beseech'd me to entreat your majesties
\LINE: To hear and see the matter.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: With all my heart; and it doth much content me
\LINE: To hear him so inclined.
\LINE: Good gentlemen, give him a further edge,
\LINE: And drive his purpose on to these delights.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: We shall, my lord.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exeunt ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Sweet Gertrude, leave us too;
\LINE: For we have closely sent for Hamlet hither,
\LINE: That he, as 'twere by accident, may here
\LINE: Affront Ophelia:
\LINE: Her father and myself, lawful espials,
\LINE: Will so bestow ourselves that, seeing, unseen,
\LINE: We may of their encounter frankly judge,
\LINE: And gather by him, as he is behaved,
\LINE: If 't be the affliction of his love or no
\LINE: That thus he suffers for.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: I shall obey you.
\LINE: And for your part, Ophelia, I do wish
\LINE: That your good beauties be the happy cause
\LINE: Of Hamlet's wildness: so shall I hope your virtues
\LINE: Will bring him to his wonted way again,
\LINE: To both your honours.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: Madam, I wish it may.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit QUEEN GERTRUDE

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: Ophelia, walk you here. Gracious, so please you,
\LINE: We will bestow ourselves.
\STAGEDIR: To OPHELIA
\LINE: Read on this book;
\LINE: That show of such an exercise may colour
\LINE: Your loneliness. We are oft to blame in this,--
\LINE: 'Tis too much proved--that with devotion's visage
\LINE: And pious action we do sugar o'er
\LINE: The devil himself.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Aside>          O, 'tis too true!>
\LINE: How smart a lash that speech doth give my conscience!
\LINE: The harlot's cheek, beautied with plastering art,
\LINE: Is not more ugly to the thing that helps it
\LINE: Than is my deed to my most painted word:
\LINE: O heavy burthen!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: I hear him coming: let's withdraw, my lord.
>

\STAGEDIR: Exeunt KING CLAUDIUS and POLONIUS
\STAGEDIR: Enter HAMLET

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: To be, or not to be: that is the question:
\LINE: Whether 'tis nobler in the mind to suffer
\LINE: The slings and arrows of outrageous fortune,
\LINE: Or to take arms against a sea of troubles,
\LINE: And by opposing end them? To die: to sleep;
\LINE: No more; and by a sleep to say we end
\LINE: The heart-ache and the thousand natural shocks
\LINE: That flesh is heir to, 'tis a consummation
\LINE: Devoutly to be wish'd. To die, to sleep;
\LINE: To sleep: perchance to dream: ay, there's the rub;
\LINE: For in that sleep of death what dreams may come
\LINE: When we have shuffled off this mortal coil,
\LINE: Must give us pause: there's the respect
\LINE: That makes calamity of so long life;
\LINE: For who would bear the whips and scorns of time,
\LINE: The oppressor's wrong, the proud man's contumely,
\LINE: The pangs of despised love, the law's delay,
\LINE: The insolence of office and the spurns
\LINE: That patient merit of the unworthy takes,
\LINE: When he himself might his quietus make
\LINE: With a bare bodkin? who would fardels bear,
\LINE: To grunt and sweat under a weary life,
\LINE: But that the dread of something after death,
\LINE: The undiscover'd country from whose bourn
\LINE: No traveller returns, puzzles the will
\LINE: And makes us rather bear those ills we have
\LINE: Than fly to others that we know not of?
\LINE: Thus conscience does make cowards of us all;
\LINE: And thus the native hue of resolution
\LINE: Is sicklied o'er with the pale cast of thought,
\LINE: And enterprises of great pith and moment
\LINE: With this regard their currents turn awry,
\LINE: And lose the name of action.--Soft you now!
\LINE: The fair Ophelia! Nymph, in thy orisons
\LINE: Be all my sins remember'd.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: Good my lord,
\LINE: How does your honour for this many a day?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I humbly thank you; well, well, well.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: My lord, I have remembrances of yours,
\LINE: That I have longed long to re-deliver;
\LINE: I pray you, now receive them.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: No, not I;
\LINE: I never gave you aught.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: My honour'd lord, you know right well you did;
\LINE: And, with them, words of so sweet breath composed
\LINE: As made the things more rich: their perfume lost,
\LINE: Take these again; for to the noble mind
\LINE: Rich gifts wax poor when givers prove unkind.
\LINE: There, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Ha, ha! are you honest?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: My lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Are you fair?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: What means your lordship?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: That if you be honest and fair, your honesty should
\LINE: admit no discourse to your beauty.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: Could beauty, my lord, have better commerce than
\LINE: with honesty?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Ay, truly; for the power of beauty will sooner
\LINE: transform honesty from what it is to a bawd than the
\LINE: force of honesty can translate beauty into his
\LINE: likeness: this was sometime a paradox, but now the
\LINE: time gives it proof. I did love you once.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: Indeed, my lord, you made me believe so.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: You should not have believed me; for virtue cannot
\LINE: so inoculate our old stock but we shall relish of
\LINE: it: I loved you not.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: I was the more deceived.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Get thee to a nunnery: why wouldst thou be a
\LINE: breeder of sinners? I am myself indifferent honest;
\LINE: but yet I could accuse me of such things that it
\LINE: were better my mother had not borne me: I am very
\LINE: proud, revengeful, ambitious, with more offences at
\LINE: my beck than I have thoughts to put them in,
\LINE: imagination to give them shape, or time to act them
\LINE: in. What should such fellows as I do crawling
\LINE: between earth and heaven? We are arrant knaves,
\LINE: all; believe none of us. Go thy ways to a nunnery.
\LINE: Where's your father?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: At home, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Let the doors be shut upon him, that he may play the
\LINE: fool no where but in's own house. Farewell.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: O, help him, you sweet heavens!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: If thou dost marry, I'll give thee this plague for
\LINE: thy dowry: be thou as chaste as ice, as pure as
\LINE: snow, thou shalt not escape calumny. Get thee to a
\LINE: nunnery, go: farewell. Or, if thou wilt needs
\LINE: marry, marry a fool; for wise men know well enough
\LINE: what monsters you make of them. To a nunnery, go,
\LINE: and quickly too. Farewell.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: O heavenly powers, restore him!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I have heard of your paintings too, well enough; God
\LINE: has given you one face, and you make yourselves
\LINE: another: you jig, you amble, and you lisp, and
\LINE: nick-name God's creatures, and make your wantonness
\LINE: your ignorance. Go to, I'll no more on't; it hath
\LINE: made me mad. I say, we will have no more marriages:
\LINE: those that are married already, all but one, shall
\LINE: live; the rest shall keep as they are. To a
\LINE: nunnery, go.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: O, what a noble mind is here o'erthrown!
\LINE: The courtier's, soldier's, scholar's, eye, tongue, sword;
\LINE: The expectancy and rose of the fair state,
\LINE: The glass of fashion and the mould of form,
\LINE: The observed of all observers, quite, quite down!
\LINE: And I, of ladies most deject and wretched,
\LINE: That suck'd the honey of his music vows,
\LINE: Now see that noble and most sovereign reason,
\LINE: Like sweet bells jangled, out of tune and harsh;
\LINE: That unmatch'd form and feature of blown youth
\LINE: Blasted with ecstasy: O, woe is me,
\LINE: To have seen what I have seen, see what I see!
>


\STAGEDIR: Re-enter KING CLAUDIUS and POLONIUS

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Love! his affections do not that way tend;
\LINE: Nor what he spake, though it lack'd form a little,
\LINE: Was not like madness. There's something in his soul,
\LINE: O'er which his melancholy sits on brood;
\LINE: And I do doubt the hatch and the disclose
\LINE: Will be some danger: which for to prevent,
\LINE: I have in quick determination
\LINE: Thus set it down: he shall with speed to England,
\LINE: For the demand of our neglected tribute
\LINE: Haply the seas and countries different
\LINE: With variable objects shall expel
\LINE: This something-settled matter in his heart,
\LINE: Whereon his brains still beating puts him thus
\LINE: From fashion of himself. What think you on't?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: It shall do well: but yet do I believe
\LINE: The origin and commencement of his grief
\LINE: Sprung from neglected love. How now, Ophelia!
\LINE: You need not tell us what Lord Hamlet said;
\LINE: We heard it all. My lord, do as you please;
\LINE: But, if you hold it fit, after the play
\LINE: Let his queen mother all alone entreat him
\LINE: To show his grief: let her be round with him;
\LINE: And I'll be placed, so please you, in the ear
\LINE: Of all their conference. If she find him not,
\LINE: To England send him, or confine him where
\LINE: Your wisdom best shall think.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: It shall be so:
\LINE: Madness in great ones must not unwatch'd go.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exeunt
>

\SCENE<\TITLE: SCENE II.  A hall in the castle.
\STAGEDIR: Enter HAMLET and Players

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Speak the speech, I pray you, as I pronounced it to
\LINE: you, trippingly on the tongue: but if you mouth it,
\LINE: as many of your players do, I had as lief the
\LINE: town-crier spoke my lines. Nor do not saw the air
\LINE: too much with your hand, thus, but use all gently;
\LINE: for in the very torrent, tempest, and, as I may say,
\LINE: the whirlwind of passion, you must acquire and beget
\LINE: a temperance that may give it smoothness. O, it
\LINE: offends me to the soul to hear a robustious
\LINE: periwig-pated fellow tear a passion to tatters, to
\LINE: very rags, to split the ears of the groundlings, who
\LINE: for the most part are capable of nothing but
\LINE: inexplicable dumbshows and noise: I would have such
\LINE: a fellow whipped for o'erdoing Termagant; it
\LINE: out-herods Herod: pray you, avoid it.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Player
\LINE: I warrant your honour.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Be not too tame neither, but let your own discretion
\LINE: be your tutor: suit the action to the word, the
\LINE: word to the action; with this special o'erstep not
\LINE: the modesty of nature: for any thing so overdone is
\LINE: from the purpose of playing, whose end, both at the
\LINE: first and now, was and is, to hold, as 'twere, the
\LINE: mirror up to nature; to show virtue her own feature,
\LINE: scorn her own image, and the very age and body of
\LINE: the time his form and pressure. Now this overdone,
\LINE: or come tardy off, though it make the unskilful
\LINE: laugh, cannot but make the judicious grieve; the
\LINE: censure of the which one must in your allowance
\LINE: o'erweigh a whole theatre of others. O, there be
\LINE: players that I have seen play, and heard others
\LINE: praise, and that highly, not to speak it profanely,
\LINE: that, neither having the accent of Christians nor
\LINE: the gait of Christian, pagan, nor man, have so
\LINE: strutted and bellowed that I have thought some of
\LINE: nature's journeymen had made men and not made them
\LINE: well, they imitated humanity so abominably.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Player
\LINE: I hope we have reformed that indifferently with us,
\LINE: sir.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: O, reform it altogether. And let those that play
\LINE: your clowns speak no more than is set down for them;
\LINE: for there be of them that will themselves laugh, to
\LINE: set on some quantity of barren spectators to laugh
\LINE: too; though, in the mean time, some necessary
\LINE: question of the play be then to be considered:
\LINE: that's villanous, and shows a most pitiful ambition
\LINE: in the fool that uses it. Go, make you ready.
\STAGEDIR: Exeunt Players
\STAGEDIR: Enter POLONIUS, ROSENCRANTZ, and GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: How now, my lord! I will the king hear this piece of work?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: And the queen too, and that presently.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Bid the players make haste.
\STAGEDIR: Exit POLONIUS
\LINE: Will you two help to hasten them?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: We will, my lord.
>

\STAGEDIR: Exeunt ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: What ho! Horatio!
>


\STAGEDIR: Enter HORATIO

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Here, sweet lord, at your service.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Horatio, thou art e'en as just a man
\LINE: As e'er my conversation coped withal.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: O, my dear lord,--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Nay, do not think I flatter;
\LINE: For what advancement may I hope from thee
\LINE: That no revenue hast but thy good spirits,
\LINE: To feed and clothe thee? Why should the poor be flatter'd?
\LINE: No, let the candied tongue lick absurd pomp,
\LINE: And crook the pregnant hinges of the knee
\LINE: Where thrift may follow fawning. Dost thou hear?
\LINE: Since my dear soul was mistress of her choice
\LINE: And could of men distinguish, her election
\LINE: Hath seal'd thee for herself; for thou hast been
\LINE: As one, in suffering all, that suffers nothing,
\LINE: A man that fortune's buffets and rewards
\LINE: Hast ta'en with equal thanks: and blest are those
\LINE: Whose blood and judgment are so well commingled,
\LINE: That they are not a pipe for fortune's finger
\LINE: To sound what stop she please. Give me that man
\LINE: That is not passion's slave, and I will wear him
\LINE: In my heart's core, ay, in my heart of heart,
\LINE: As I do thee.--Something too much of this.--
\LINE: There is a play to-night before the king;
\LINE: One scene of it comes near the circumstance
\LINE: Which I have told thee of my father's death:
\LINE: I prithee, when thou seest that act afoot,
\LINE: Even with the very comment of thy soul
\LINE: Observe mine uncle: if his occulted guilt
\LINE: Do not itself unkennel in one speech,
\LINE: It is a damned ghost that we have seen,
\LINE: And my imaginations are as foul
\LINE: As Vulcan's stithy. Give him heedful note;
\LINE: For I mine eyes will rivet to his face,
\LINE: And after we will both our judgments join
\LINE: In censure of his seeming.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Well, my lord:
\LINE: If he steal aught the whilst this play is playing,
\LINE: And 'scape detecting, I will pay the theft.
>

\SPEECH<
