\LINE: O, my lord, if my duty be too bold, my love is too
\LINE: unmannerly.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I do not well understand that. Will you play upon
\LINE: this pipe?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: My lord, I cannot.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I pray you.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: Believe me, I cannot.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I do beseech you.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: I know no touch of it, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: 'Tis as easy as lying: govern these ventages with
\LINE: your lingers and thumb, give it breath with your
\LINE: mouth, and it will discourse most eloquent music.
\LINE: Look you, these are the stops.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: But these cannot I command to any utterance of
\LINE: harmony; I have not the skill.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Why, look you now, how unworthy a thing you make of
\LINE: me! You would play upon me; you would seem to know
\LINE: my stops; you would pluck out the heart of my
\LINE: mystery; you would sound me from my lowest note to
\LINE: the top of my compass: and there is much music,
\LINE: excellent voice, in this little organ; yet cannot
\LINE: you make it speak. 'Sblood, do you think I am
\LINE: easier to be played on than a pipe? Call me what
\LINE: instrument you will, though you can fret me, yet you
\LINE: cannot play upon me.
\STAGEDIR: Enter POLONIUS
\LINE: God bless you, sir!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: My lord, the queen would speak with you, and
\LINE: presently.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Do you see yonder cloud that's almost in shape of a camel?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: By the mass, and 'tis like a camel, indeed.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Methinks it is like a weasel.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: It is backed like a weasel.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Or like a whale?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: Very like a whale.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Then I will come to my mother by and by. They fool
\LINE: me to the top of my bent. I will come by and by.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: I will say so.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: By and by is easily said.
\STAGEDIR: Exit POLONIUS
\LINE: Leave me, friends.
\STAGEDIR: Exeunt all but HAMLET
\LINE: Tis now the very witching time of night,
\LINE: When churchyards yawn and hell itself breathes out
\LINE: Contagion to this world: now could I drink hot blood,
\LINE: And do such bitter business as the day
\LINE: Would quake to look on. Soft! now to my mother.
\LINE: O heart, lose not thy nature; let not ever
\LINE: The soul of Nero enter this firm bosom:
\LINE: Let me be cruel, not unnatural:
\LINE: I will speak daggers to her, but use none;
\LINE: My tongue and soul in this be hypocrites;
\LINE: How in my words soever she be shent,
\LINE: To give them seals never, my soul, consent!
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit
>

\SCENE<\TITLE: SCENE III.  A room in the castle.
\STAGEDIR: Enter KING CLAUDIUS, ROSENCRANTZ, and GUILDENSTERN

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: I like him not, nor stands it safe with us
\LINE: To let his madness range. Therefore prepare you;
\LINE: I your commission will forthwith dispatch,
\LINE: And he to England shall along with you:
\LINE: The terms of our estate may not endure
\LINE: Hazard so dangerous as doth hourly grow
\LINE: Out of his lunacies.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: We will ourselves provide:
\LINE: Most holy and religious fear it is
\LINE: To keep those many many bodies safe
\LINE: That live and feed upon your majesty.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: The single and peculiar life is bound,
\LINE: With all the strength and armour of the mind,
\LINE: To keep itself from noyance; but much more
\LINE: That spirit upon whose weal depend and rest
\LINE: The lives of many. The cease of majesty
\LINE: Dies not alone; but, like a gulf, doth draw
\LINE: What's near it with it: it is a massy wheel,
\LINE: Fix'd on the summit of the highest mount,
\LINE: To whose huge spokes ten thousand lesser things
\LINE: Are mortised and adjoin'd; which, when it falls,
\LINE: Each small annexment, petty consequence,
\LINE: Attends the boisterous ruin. Never alone
\LINE: Did the king sigh, but with a general groan.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Arm you, I pray you, to this speedy voyage;
\LINE: For we will fetters put upon this fear,
\LINE: Which now goes too free-footed.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: We will haste us.
>

\STAGEDIR: Exeunt ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN
\STAGEDIR: Enter POLONIUS

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: My lord, he's going to his mother's closet:
\LINE: Behind the arras I'll convey myself,
\LINE: To hear the process; and warrant she'll tax him home:
\LINE: And, as you said, and wisely was it said,
\LINE: 'Tis meet that some more audience than a mother,
\LINE: Since nature makes them partial, should o'erhear
\LINE: The speech, of vantage. Fare you well, my liege:
\LINE: I'll call upon you ere you go to bed,
\LINE: And tell you what I know.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Thanks, dear my lord.
\STAGEDIR: Exit POLONIUS
\LINE: O, my offence is rank it smells to heaven;
\LINE: It hath the primal eldest curse upon't,
\LINE: A brother's murder. Pray can I not,
\LINE: Though inclination be as sharp as will:
\LINE: My stronger guilt defeats my strong intent;
\LINE: And, like a man to double business bound,
\LINE: I stand in pause where I shall first begin,
\LINE: And both neglect. What if this cursed hand
\LINE: Were thicker than itself with brother's blood,
\LINE: Is there not rain enough in the sweet heavens
\LINE: To wash it white as snow? Whereto serves mercy
\LINE: But to confront the visage of offence?
\LINE: And what's in prayer but this two-fold force,
\LINE: To be forestalled ere we come to fall,
\LINE: Or pardon'd being down? Then I'll look up;
\LINE: My fault is past. But, O, what form of prayer
\LINE: Can serve my turn? 'Forgive me my foul murder'?
\LINE: That cannot be; since I am still possess'd
\LINE: Of those effects for which I did the murder,
\LINE: My crown, mine own ambition and my queen.
\LINE: May one be pardon'd and retain the offence?
\LINE: In the corrupted currents of this world
\LINE: Offence's gilded hand may shove by justice,
\LINE: And oft 'tis seen the wicked prize itself
\LINE: Buys out the law: but 'tis not so above;
\LINE: There is no shuffling, there the action lies
\LINE: In his true nature; and we ourselves compell'd,
\LINE: Even to the teeth and forehead of our faults,
\LINE: To give in evidence. What then? what rests?
\LINE: Try what repentance can: what can it not?
\LINE: Yet what can it when one can not repent?
\LINE: O wretched state! O bosom black as death!
\LINE: O limed soul, that, struggling to be free,
\LINE: Art more engaged! Help, angels! Make assay!
\LINE: Bow, stubborn knees; and, heart with strings of steel,
\LINE: Be soft as sinews of the newborn babe!
\LINE: All may be well.
>

\STAGEDIR: Retires and kneels
\STAGEDIR: Enter HAMLET

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Now might I do it pat, now he is praying;
\LINE: And now I'll do't. And so he goes to heaven;
\LINE: And so am I revenged. That would be scann'd:
\LINE: A villain kills my father; and for that,
\LINE: I, his sole son, do this same villain send
\LINE: To heaven.
\LINE: O, this is hire and salary, not revenge.
\LINE: He took my father grossly, full of bread;
\LINE: With all his crimes broad blown, as flush as May;
\LINE: And how his audit stands who knows save heaven?
\LINE: But in our circumstance and course of thought,
\LINE: 'Tis heavy with him: and am I then revenged,
\LINE: To take him in the purging of his soul,
\LINE: When he is fit and season'd for his passage?
\LINE: No!
\LINE: Up, sword; and know thou a more horrid hent:
\LINE: When he is drunk asleep, or in his rage,
\LINE: Or in the incestuous pleasure of his bed;
\LINE: At gaming, swearing, or about some act
\LINE: That has no relish of salvation in't;
\LINE: Then trip him, that his heels may kick at heaven,
\LINE: And that his soul may be as damn'd and black
\LINE: As hell, whereto it goes. My mother stays:
\LINE: This physic but prolongs thy sickly days.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Rising>  My words fly up, my thoughts remain below:>
\LINE: Words without thoughts never to heaven go.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit
>

\SCENE<\TITLE: SCENE IV.  The Queen's closet.
\STAGEDIR: Enter QUEEN MARGARET and POLONIUS

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE: He will come straight. Look you lay home to him:
\LINE: Tell him his pranks have been too broad to bear with,
\LINE: And that your grace hath screen'd and stood between
\LINE: Much heat and him. I'll sconce me even here.
\LINE: Pray you, be round with him.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Within>  Mother, mother, mother!>
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: I'll warrant you,
\LINE: Fear me not: withdraw, I hear him coming.
>

\STAGEDIR: POLONIUS hides behind the arras
\STAGEDIR: Enter HAMLET

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Now, mother, what's the matter?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Hamlet, thou hast thy father much offended.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Mother, you have my father much offended.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Come, come, you answer with an idle tongue.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Go, go, you question with a wicked tongue.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Why, how now, Hamlet!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: What's the matter now?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Have you forgot me?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: No, by the rood, not so:
\LINE: You are the queen, your husband's brother's wife;
\LINE: And--would it were not so!--you are my mother.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Nay, then, I'll set those to you that can speak.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Come, come, and sit you down; you shall not budge;
\LINE: You go not till I set you up a glass
\LINE: Where you may see the inmost part of you.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: What wilt thou do? thou wilt not murder me?
\LINE: Help, help, ho!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Behind>  What, ho! help, help, help!>
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Drawing>  How now! a rat? Dead, for a ducat, dead!>
>


\STAGEDIR: Makes a pass through the arras

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LORD POLONIUS
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Behind>  O, I am slain!>
>


\STAGEDIR: Falls and dies

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: O me, what hast thou done?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Nay, I know not:
\LINE: Is it the king?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: O, what a rash and bloody deed is this!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: A bloody deed! almost as bad, good mother,
\LINE: As kill a king, and marry with his brother.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: As kill a king!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Ay, lady, 'twas my word.
\STAGEDIR: Lifts up the array and discovers POLONIUS
\LINE: Thou wretched, rash, intruding fool, farewell!
\LINE: I took thee for thy better: take thy fortune;
\LINE: Thou find'st to be too busy is some danger.
\LINE: Leave wringing of your hands: peace! sit you down,
\LINE: And let me wring your heart; for so I shall,
\LINE: If it be made of penetrable stuff,
\LINE: If damned custom have not brass'd it so
\LINE: That it is proof and bulwark against sense.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: What have I done, that thou darest wag thy tongue
\LINE: In noise so rude against me?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Such an act
\LINE: That blurs the grace and blush of modesty,
\LINE: Calls virtue hypocrite, takes off the rose
\LINE: From the fair forehead of an innocent love
\LINE: And sets a blister there, makes marriage-vows
\LINE: As false as dicers' oaths: O, such a deed
\LINE: As from the body of contraction plucks
\LINE: The very soul, and sweet religion makes
\LINE: A rhapsody of words: heaven's face doth glow:
\LINE: Yea, this solidity and compound mass,
\LINE: With tristful visage, as against the doom,
\LINE: Is thought-sick at the act.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Ay me, what act,
\LINE: That roars so loud, and thunders in the index?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Look here, upon this picture, and on this,
\LINE: The counterfeit presentment of two brothers.
\LINE: See, what a grace was seated on this brow;
\LINE: Hyperion's curls; the front of Jove himself;
\LINE: An eye like Mars, to threaten and command;
\LINE: A station like the herald Mercury
\LINE: New-lighted on a heaven-kissing hill;
\LINE: A combination and a form indeed,
\LINE: Where every god did seem to set his seal,
\LINE: To give the world assurance of a man:
\LINE: This was your husband. Look you now, what follows:
\LINE: Here is your husband; like a mildew'd ear,
\LINE: Blasting his wholesome brother. Have you eyes?
\LINE: Could you on this fair mountain leave to feed,
\LINE: And batten on this moor? Ha! have you eyes?
\LINE: You cannot call it love; for at your age
\LINE: The hey-day in the blood is tame, it's humble,
\LINE: And waits upon the judgment: and what judgment
\LINE: Would step from this to this? Sense, sure, you have,
\LINE: Else could you not have motion; but sure, that sense
\LINE: Is apoplex'd; for madness would not err,
\LINE: Nor sense to ecstasy was ne'er so thrall'd
\LINE: But it reserved some quantity of choice,
\LINE: To serve in such a difference. What devil was't
\LINE: That thus hath cozen'd you at hoodman-blind?
\LINE: Eyes without feeling, feeling without sight,
\LINE: Ears without hands or eyes, smelling sans all,
\LINE: Or but a sickly part of one true sense
\LINE: Could not so mope.
\LINE: O shame! where is thy blush? Rebellious hell,
\LINE: If thou canst mutine in a matron's bones,
\LINE: To flaming youth let virtue be as wax,
\LINE: And melt in her own fire: proclaim no shame
\LINE: When the compulsive ardour gives the charge,
\LINE: Since frost itself as actively doth burn
\LINE: And reason panders will.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: O Hamlet, speak no more:
\LINE: Thou turn'st mine eyes into my very soul;
\LINE: And there I see such black and grained spots
\LINE: As will not leave their tinct.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Nay, but to live
\LINE: In the rank sweat of an enseamed bed,
\LINE: Stew'd in corruption, honeying and making love
\LINE: Over the nasty sty,--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: O, speak to me no more;
\LINE: These words, like daggers, enter in mine ears;
\LINE: No more, sweet Hamlet!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: A murderer and a villain;
\LINE: A slave that is not twentieth part the tithe
\LINE: Of your precedent lord; a vice of kings;
\LINE: A cutpurse of the empire and the rule,
\LINE: That from a shelf the precious diadem stole,
\LINE: And put it in his pocket!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: No more!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: A king of shreds and patches,--
\STAGEDIR: Enter Ghost
\LINE: Save me, and hover o'er me with your wings,
\LINE: You heavenly guards! What would your gracious figure?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Alas, he's mad!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Do you not come your tardy son to chide,
\LINE: That, lapsed in time and passion, lets go by
\LINE: The important acting of your dread command? O, say!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Ghost
\LINE: Do not forget: this visitation
\LINE: Is but to whet thy almost blunted purpose.
\LINE: But, look, amazement on thy mother sits:
\LINE: O, step between her and her fighting soul:
\LINE: Conceit in weakest bodies strongest works:
\LINE: Speak to her, Hamlet.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: How is it with you, lady?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Alas, how is't with you,
\LINE: That you do bend your eye on vacancy
\LINE: And with the incorporal air do hold discourse?
\LINE: Forth at your eyes your spirits wildly peep;
\LINE: And, as the sleeping soldiers in the alarm,
\LINE: Your bedded hair, like life in excrements,
\LINE: Starts up, and stands on end. O gentle son,
\LINE: Upon the heat and flame of thy distemper
\LINE: Sprinkle cool patience. Whereon do you look?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: On him, on him! Look you, how pale he glares!
\LINE: His form and cause conjoin'd, preaching to stones,
\LINE: Would make them capable. Do not look upon me;
\LINE: Lest with this piteous action you convert
\LINE: My stern effects: then what I have to do
\LINE: Will want true colour; tears perchance for blood.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: To whom do you speak this?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Do you see nothing there?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Nothing at all; yet all that is I see.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Nor did you nothing hear?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: No, nothing but ourselves.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Why, look you there! look, how it steals away!
\LINE: My father, in his habit as he lived!
\LINE: Look, where he goes, even now, out at the portal!
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit Ghost

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: This the very coinage of your brain:
\LINE: This bodiless creation ecstasy
\LINE: Is very cunning in.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Ecstasy!
\LINE: My pulse, as yours, doth temperately keep time,
\LINE: And makes as healthful music: it is not madness
\LINE: That I have utter'd: bring me to the test,
\LINE: And I the matter will re-word; which madness
\LINE: Would gambol from. Mother, for love of grace,
\LINE: Lay not that mattering unction to your soul,
\LINE: That not your trespass, but my madness speaks:
\LINE: It will but skin and film the ulcerous place,
\LINE: Whilst rank corruption, mining all within,
\LINE: Infects unseen. Confess yourself to heaven;
\LINE: Repent what's past; avoid what is to come;
\LINE: And do not spread the compost on the weeds,
\LINE: To make them ranker. Forgive me this my virtue;
\LINE: For in the fatness of these pursy times
\LINE: Virtue itself of vice must pardon beg,
\LINE: Yea, curb and woo for leave to do him good.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: O Hamlet, thou hast cleft my heart in twain.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: O, throw away the worser part of it,
\LINE: And live the purer with the other half.
\LINE: Good night: but go not to mine uncle's bed;
\LINE: Assume a virtue, if you have it not.
\LINE: That monster, custom, who all sense doth eat,
\LINE: Of habits devil, is angel yet in this,
\LINE: That to the use of actions fair and good
\LINE: He likewise gives a frock or livery,
\LINE: That aptly is put on. Refrain to-night,
\LINE: And that shall lend a kind of easiness
\LINE: To the next abstinence: the next more easy;
\LINE: For use almost can change the stamp of nature,
\LINE: And either ... the devil, or throw him out
\LINE: With wondrous potency. Once more, good night:
\LINE: And when you are desirous to be bless'd,
\LINE: I'll blessing beg of you. For this same lord,
\STAGEDIR: Pointing to POLONIUS
\LINE: I do repent: but heaven hath pleased it so,
\LINE: To punish me with this and this with me,
\LINE: That I must be their scourge and minister.
\LINE: I will bestow him, and will answer well
\LINE: The death I gave him. So, again, good night.
\LINE: I must be cruel, only to be kind:
\LINE: Thus bad begins and worse remains behind.
\LINE: One word more, good lady.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: What shall I do?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Not this, by no means, that I bid you do:
\LINE: Let the bloat king tempt you again to bed;
\LINE: Pinch wanton on your cheek; call you his mouse;
\LINE: And let him, for a pair of reechy kisses,
\LINE: Or paddling in your neck with his damn'd fingers,
\LINE: Make you to ravel all this matter out,
\LINE: That I essentially am not in madness,
\LINE: But mad in craft. 'Twere good you let him know;
\LINE: For who, that's but a queen, fair, sober, wise,
\LINE: Would from a paddock, from a bat, a gib,
\LINE: Such dear concernings hide? who would do so?
\LINE: No, in despite of sense and secrecy,
\LINE: Unpeg the basket on the house's top.
\LINE: Let the birds fly, and, like the famous ape,
\LINE: To try conclusions, in the basket creep,
\LINE: And break your own neck down.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Be thou assured, if words be made of breath,
\LINE: And breath of life, I have no life to breathe
\LINE: What thou hast said to me.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I must to England; you know that?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Alack,
\LINE: I had forgot: 'tis so concluded on.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: There's letters seal'd: and my two schoolfellows,
\LINE: Whom I will trust as I will adders fang'd,
\LINE: They bear the mandate; they must sweep my way,
\LINE: And marshal me to knavery. Let it work;
\LINE: For 'tis the sport to have the engineer
\LINE: Hoist with his own petard: and 't shall go hard
\LINE: But I will delve one yard below their mines,
\LINE: And blow them at the moon: O, 'tis most sweet,
\LINE: When in one line two crafts directly meet.
\LINE: This man shall set me packing:
\LINE: I'll lug the guts into the neighbour room.
\LINE: Mother, good night. Indeed this counsellor
\LINE: Is now most still, most secret and most grave,
\LINE: Who was in life a foolish prating knave.
\LINE: Come, sir, to draw toward an end with you.
\LINE: Good night, mother.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exeunt severally; HAMLET dragging in POLONIUS
>

>

\ACT<\TITLE: ACT IV

\SCENE<\TITLE: SCENE I.  A room in the castle.
\STAGEDIR<Enter KING CLAUDIUS, QUEEN GERTRUDE, ROSENCRANTZ,
and GUILDENSTERN>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: There's matter in these sighs, these profound heaves:
\LINE: You must translate: 'tis fit we understand them.
\LINE: Where is your son?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Bestow this place on us a little while.
\STAGEDIR: Exeunt ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: Ah, my good lord, what have I seen to-night!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: What, Gertrude? How does Hamlet?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Mad as the sea and wind, when both contend
\LINE: Which is the mightier: in his lawless fit,
\LINE: Behind the arras hearing something stir,
\LINE: Whips out his rapier, cries, 'A rat, a rat!'
\LINE: And, in this brainish apprehension, kills
\LINE: The unseen good old man.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: O heavy deed!
\LINE: It had been so with us, had we been there:
\LINE: His liberty is full of threats to all;
\LINE: To you yourself, to us, to every one.
\LINE: Alas, how shall this bloody deed be answer'd?
\LINE: It will be laid to us, whose providence
\LINE: Should have kept short, restrain'd and out of haunt,
\LINE: This mad young man: but so much was our love,
\LINE: We would not understand what was most fit;
\LINE: But, like the owner of a foul disease,
\LINE: To keep it from divulging, let it feed
\LINE: Even on the pith of Life. Where is he gone?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: To draw apart the body he hath kill'd:
\LINE: O'er whom his very madness, like some ore
\LINE: Among a mineral of metals base,
\LINE: Shows itself pure; he weeps for what is done.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: O Gertrude, come away!
\LINE: The sun no sooner shall the mountains touch,
\LINE: But we will ship him hence: and this vile deed
\LINE: We must, with all our majesty and skill,
\LINE: Both countenance and excuse. Ho, Guildenstern!
\STAGEDIR: Re-enter ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: Friends both, go join you with some further aid:
\LINE: Hamlet in madness hath Polonius slain,
\LINE: And from his mother's closet hath he dragg'd him:
\LINE: Go seek him out; speak fair, and bring the body
\LINE: Into the chapel. I pray you, haste in this.
\STAGEDIR: Exeunt ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: Come, Gertrude, we'll call up our wisest friends;
\LINE: And let them know, both what we mean to do,
\LINE: And what's untimely done...
\LINE: Whose whisper o'er the world's diameter,
\LINE: As level as the cannon to his blank,
\LINE: Transports his poison'd shot, may miss our name,
\LINE: And hit the woundless air. O, come away!
\LINE: My soul is full of discord and dismay.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exeunt
>

\SCENE<\TITLE: SCENE II.  Another room in the castle.
\STAGEDIR: Enter HAMLET

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Safely stowed.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Within>  Hamlet! Lord Hamlet!>
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: What noise? who calls on Hamlet?
\LINE: O, here they come.
>


\STAGEDIR: Enter ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: What have you done, my lord, with the dead body?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Compounded it with dust, whereto 'tis kin.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Tell us where 'tis, that we may take it thence
\LINE: And bear it to the chapel.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Do not believe it.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Believe what?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: That I can keep your counsel and not mine own.
\LINE: Besides, to be demanded of a sponge! what
\LINE: replication should be made by the son of a king?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Take you me for a sponge, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Ay, sir, that soaks up the king's countenance, his
\LINE: rewards, his authorities. But such officers do the
\LINE: king best service in the end: he keeps them, like
\LINE: an ape, in the corner of his jaw; first mouthed, to
\LINE: be last swallowed: when he needs what you have
\LINE: gleaned, it is but squeezing you, and, sponge, you
\LINE: shall be dry again.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: I understand you not, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I am glad of it: a knavish speech sleeps in a
\LINE: foolish ear.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: My lord, you must tell us where the body is, and go
\LINE: with us to the king.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: The body is with the king, but the king is not with
\LINE: the body. The king is a thing--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: A thing, my lord!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Of nothing: bring me to him. Hide fox, and all after.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exeunt
>

\SCENE<\TITLE: SCENE III.  Another room in the castle.
\STAGEDIR: Enter KING CLAUDIUS, attended

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: I have sent to seek him, and to find the body.
\LINE: How dangerous is it that this man goes loose!
\LINE: Yet must not we put the strong law on him:
\LINE: He's loved of the distracted multitude,
\LINE: Who like not in their judgment, but their eyes;
\LINE: And where tis so, the offender's scourge is weigh'd,
\LINE: But never the offence. To bear all smooth and even,
\LINE: This sudden sending him away must seem
\LINE: Deliberate pause: diseases desperate grown
\LINE: By desperate appliance are relieved,
\LINE: Or not at all.
\STAGEDIR: Enter ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: How now! what hath befall'n?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Where the dead body is bestow'd, my lord,
\LINE: We cannot get from him.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: But where is he?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Without, my lord; guarded, to know your pleasure.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Bring him before us.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Ho, Guildenstern! bring in my lord.
>


\STAGEDIR: Enter HAMLET and GUILDENSTERN

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Now, Hamlet, where's Polonius?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: At supper.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: At supper! where?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Not where he eats, but where he is eaten: a certain
\LINE: convocation of politic worms are e'en at him. Your
\LINE: worm is your only emperor for diet: we fat all
\LINE: creatures else to fat us, and we fat ourselves for
\LINE: maggots: your fat king and your lean beggar is but
\LINE: variable service, two dishes, but to one table:
\LINE: that's the end.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Alas, alas!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: A man may fish with the worm that hath eat of a
\LINE: king, and cat of the fish that hath fed of that worm.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: What dost you mean by this?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Nothing but to show you how a king may go a
\LINE: progress through the guts of a beggar.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Where is Polonius?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: In heaven; send hither to see: if your messenger
\LINE: find him not there, seek him i' the other place
\LINE: yourself. But indeed, if you find him not within
\LINE: this month, you shall nose him as you go up the
\LINE: stairs into the lobby.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Go seek him there.
>


\STAGEDIR: To some Attendants

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: He will stay till ye come.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exeunt Attendants

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Hamlet, this deed, for thine especial safety,--
\LINE: Which we do tender, as we dearly grieve
\LINE: For that which thou hast done,--must send thee hence
\LINE: With fiery quickness: therefore prepare thyself;
\LINE: The bark is ready, and the wind at help,
\LINE: The associates tend, and every thing is bent
\LINE: For England.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: For England!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Ay, Hamlet.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Good.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: So is it, if thou knew'st our purposes.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I see a cherub that sees them. But, come; for
\LINE: England! Farewell, dear mother.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Thy loving father, Hamlet.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: My mother: father and mother is man and wife; man
\LINE: and wife is one flesh; and so, my mother. Come, for England!
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Follow him at foot; tempt him with speed aboard;
\LINE: Delay it not; I'll have him hence to-night:
\LINE: Away! for every thing is seal'd and done
\LINE: That else leans on the affair: pray you, make haste.
\STAGEDIR: Exeunt ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN
\LINE: And, England, if my love thou hold'st at aught--
\LINE: As my great power thereof may give thee sense,
\LINE: Since yet thy cicatrice looks raw and red
\LINE: After the Danish sword, and thy free awe
\LINE: Pays homage to us--thou mayst not coldly set
\LINE: Our sovereign process; which imports at full,
\LINE: By letters congruing to that effect,
\LINE: The present death of Hamlet. Do it, England;
\LINE: For like the hectic in my blood he rages,
\LINE: And thou must cure me: till I know 'tis done,
\LINE: Howe'er my haps, my joys were ne'er begun.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit
>

\SCENE<\TITLE: SCENE IV.  A plain in Denmark.
\STAGEDIR: Enter FORTINBRAS, a Captain, and Soldiers, marching

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: PRINCE FORTINBRAS
\LINE: Go, captain, from me greet the Danish king;
\LINE: Tell him that, by his licence, Fortinbras
\LINE: Craves the conveyance of a promised march
\LINE: Over his kingdom. You know the rendezvous.
\LINE: If that his majesty would aught with us,
\LINE: We shall express our duty in his eye;
\LINE: And let him know so.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Captain
\LINE: I will do't, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: PRINCE FORTINBRAS
\LINE: Go softly on.
>

\STAGEDIR: Exeunt FORTINBRAS and Soldiers
\STAGEDIR: Enter HAMLET, ROSENCRANTZ, GUILDENSTERN, and others

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Good sir, whose powers are these?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Captain
\LINE: They are of Norway, sir.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: How purposed, sir, I pray you?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Captain
\LINE: Against some part of Poland.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Who commands them, sir?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Captain
\LINE: The nephews to old Norway, Fortinbras.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Goes it against the main of Poland, sir,
\LINE: Or for some frontier?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Captain
\LINE: Truly to speak, and with no addition,
\LINE: We go to gain a little patch of ground
\LINE: That hath in it no profit but the name.
\LINE: To pay five ducats, five, I would not farm it;
\LINE: Nor will it yield to Norway or the Pole
\LINE: A ranker rate, should it be sold in fee.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Why, then the Polack never will defend it.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Captain
\LINE: Yes, it is already garrison'd.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Two thousand souls and twenty thousand ducats
\LINE: Will not debate the question of this straw:
\LINE: This is the imposthume of much wealth and peace,
\LINE: That inward breaks, and shows no cause without
\LINE: Why the man dies. I humbly thank you, sir.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Captain
\LINE: God be wi' you, sir.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: ROSENCRANTZ
\LINE: Wilt please you go, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I'll be with you straight go a little before.
\STAGEDIR: Exeunt all except HAMLET
\LINE: How all occasions do inform against me,
\LINE: And spur my dull revenge! What is a man,
\LINE: If his chief good and market of his time
\LINE: Be but to sleep and feed? a beast, no more.
\LINE: Sure, he that made us with such large discourse,
\LINE: Looking before and after, gave us not
\LINE: That capability and god-like reason
\LINE: To fust in us unused. Now, whether it be
\LINE: Bestial oblivion, or some craven scruple
\LINE: Of thinking too precisely on the event,
\LINE: A thought which, quarter'd, hath but one part wisdom
\LINE: And ever three parts coward, I do not know
\LINE: Why yet I live to say 'This thing's to do;'
\LINE: Sith I have cause and will and strength and means
\LINE: To do't. Examples gross as earth exhort me:
\LINE: Witness this army of such mass and charge
\LINE: Led by a delicate and tender prince,
\LINE: Whose spirit with divine ambition puff'd
\LINE: Makes mouths at the invisible event,
\LINE: Exposing what is mortal and unsure
\LINE: To all that fortune, death and danger dare,
\LINE: Even for an egg-shell. Rightly to be great
\LINE: Is not to stir without great argument,
\LINE: But greatly to find quarrel in a straw
\LINE: When honour's at the stake. How stand I then,
\LINE: That have a father kill'd, a mother stain'd,
\LINE: Excitements of my reason and my blood,
\LINE: And let all sleep? while, to my shame, I see
\LINE: The imminent death of twenty thousand men,
\LINE: That, for a fantasy and trick of fame,
\LINE: Go to their graves like beds, fight for a plot
\LINE: Whereon the numbers cannot try the cause,
\LINE: Which is not tomb enough and continent
\LINE: To hide the slain? O, from this time forth,
\LINE: My thoughts be bloody, or be nothing worth!
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit
>

\SCENE<\TITLE: SCENE V.  Elsinore. A room in the castle.
\STAGEDIR: Enter QUEEN GERTRUDE, HORATIO, and a Gentleman

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: I will not speak with her.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Gentleman
\LINE: She is importunate, indeed distract:
\LINE: Her mood will needs be pitied.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: What would she have?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Gentleman
\LINE: She speaks much of her father; says she hears
\LINE: There's tricks i' the world; and hems, and beats her heart;
\LINE: Spurns enviously at straws; speaks things in doubt,
\LINE: That carry but half sense: her speech is nothing,
\LINE: Yet the unshaped use of it doth move
\LINE: The hearers to collection; they aim at it,
\LINE: And botch the words up fit to their own thoughts;
\LINE: Which, as her winks, and nods, and gestures
\LINE: yield them,
\LINE: Indeed would make one think there might be thought,
\LINE: Though nothing sure, yet much unhappily.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: 'Twere good she were spoken with; for she may strew
\LINE: Dangerous conjectures in ill-breeding minds.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Let her come in.
\STAGEDIR: Exit HORATIO
\LINE: To my sick soul, as sin's true nature is,
\LINE: Each toy seems prologue to some great amiss:
\LINE: So full of artless jealousy is guilt,
\LINE: It spills itself in fearing to be spilt.
>


\STAGEDIR: Re-enter HORATIO, with OPHELIA

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: Where is the beauteous majesty of Denmark?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: How now, Ophelia!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Sings>>
\LINE: How should I your true love know
\LINE: From another one?
\LINE: By his cockle hat and staff,
\LINE: And his sandal shoon.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Alas, sweet lady, what imports this song?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: Say you? nay, pray you, mark.
\STAGEDIR: Sings
\LINE: He is dead and gone, lady,
\LINE: He is dead and gone;
\LINE: At his head a grass-green turf,
\LINE: At his heels a stone.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Nay, but, Ophelia,--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: Pray you, mark.
\STAGEDIR: Sings
\LINE: White his shroud as the mountain snow,--
>


\STAGEDIR: Enter KING CLAUDIUS

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Alas, look here, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Sings>>
\LINE: Larded with sweet flowers
\LINE: Which bewept to the grave did go
\LINE: With true-love showers.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: How do you, pretty lady?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: Well, God 'ild you! They say the owl was a baker's
\LINE: daughter. Lord, we know what we are, but know not
\LINE: what we may be. God be at your table!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Conceit upon her father.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: Pray you, let's have no words of this; but when they
\LINE: ask you what it means, say you this:
\STAGEDIR: Sings
\LINE: To-morrow is Saint Valentine's day,
\LINE: All in the morning betime,
\LINE: And I a maid at your window,
\LINE: To be your Valentine.
\LINE: Then up he rose, and donn'd his clothes,
\LINE: And dupp'd the chamber-door;
\LINE: Let in the maid, that out a maid
\LINE: Never departed more.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Pretty Ophelia!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: Indeed, la, without an oath, I'll make an end on't:
\STAGEDIR: Sings
\LINE: By Gis and by Saint Charity,
\LINE: Alack, and fie for shame!
\LINE: Young men will do't, if they come to't;
\LINE: By cock, they are to blame.
\LINE: Quoth she, before you tumbled me,
\LINE: You promised me to wed.
\LINE: So would I ha' done, by yonder sun,
\LINE: An thou hadst not come to my bed.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: How long hath she been thus?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: I hope all will be well. We must be patient: but I
\LINE: cannot choose but weep, to think they should lay him
\LINE: i' the cold ground. My brother shall know of it:
\LINE: and so I thank you for your good counsel. Come, my
\LINE: coach! Good night, ladies; good night, sweet ladies;
\LINE: good night, good night.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Follow her close; give her good watch,
\LINE: I pray you.
\STAGEDIR: Exit HORATIO
\LINE: O, this is the poison of deep grief; it springs
\LINE: All from her father's death. O Gertrude, Gertrude,
\LINE: When sorrows come, they come not single spies
\LINE: But in battalions. First, her father slain:
\LINE: Next, your son gone; and he most violent author
\LINE: Of his own just remove: the people muddied,
\LINE: Thick and unwholesome in their thoughts and whispers,
\LINE: For good Polonius' death; and we have done but greenly,
\LINE: In hugger-mugger to inter him: poor Ophelia
\LINE: Divided from herself and her fair judgment,
\LINE: Without the which we are pictures, or mere beasts:
\LINE: Last, and as much containing as all these,
\LINE: Her brother is in secret come from France;
\LINE: Feeds on his wonder, keeps himself in clouds,
\LINE: And wants not buzzers to infect his ear
\LINE: With pestilent speeches of his father's death;
\LINE: Wherein necessity, of matter beggar'd,
\LINE: Will nothing stick our person to arraign
\LINE: In ear and ear. O my dear Gertrude, this,
\LINE: Like to a murdering-piece, in many places
\LINE: Gives me superfluous death.
>


\STAGEDIR: A noise within

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Alack, what noise is this?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Where are my Switzers? Let them guard the door.
\STAGEDIR: Enter another Gentleman
\LINE: What is the matter?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Gentleman
\LINE: Save yourself, my lord:
\LINE: The ocean, overpeering of his list,
\LINE: Eats not the flats with more impetuous haste
\LINE: Than young Laertes, in a riotous head,
\LINE: O'erbears your officers. The rabble call him lord;
\LINE: And, as the world were now but to begin,
\LINE: Antiquity forgot, custom not known,
\LINE: The ratifiers and props of every word,
\LINE: They cry 'Choose we: Laertes shall be king:'
\LINE: Caps, hands, and tongues, applaud it to the clouds:
\LINE: 'Laertes shall be king, Laertes king!'
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: How cheerfully on the false trail they cry!
\LINE: O, this is counter, you false Danish dogs!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: The doors are broke.
>

\STAGEDIR: Noise within
\STAGEDIR: Enter LAERTES, armed; Danes following

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Where is this king? Sirs, stand you all without.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Danes
\LINE: No, let's come in.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: I pray you, give me leave.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Danes
\LINE: We will, we will.
>


\STAGEDIR: They retire without the door

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: I thank you: keep the door. O thou vile king,
\LINE: Give me my father!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Calmly, good Laertes.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: That drop of blood that's calm proclaims me bastard,
\LINE: Cries cuckold to my father, brands the harlot
\LINE: Even here, between the chaste unsmirched brow
\LINE: Of my true mother.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: What is the cause, Laertes,
\LINE: That thy rebellion looks so giant-like?
\LINE: Let him go, Gertrude; do not fear our person:
\LINE: There's such divinity doth hedge a king,
\LINE: That treason can but peep to what it would,
\LINE: Acts little of his will. Tell me, Laertes,
\LINE: Why thou art thus incensed. Let him go, Gertrude.
\LINE: Speak, man.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Where is my father?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Dead.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: But not by him.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Let him demand his fill.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: How came he dead? I'll not be juggled with:
\LINE: To hell, allegiance! vows, to the blackest devil!
\LINE: Conscience and grace, to the profoundest pit!
\LINE: I dare damnation. To this point I stand,
\LINE: That both the worlds I give to negligence,
\LINE: Let come what comes; only I'll be revenged
\LINE: Most thoroughly for my father.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Who shall stay you?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: My will, not all the world:
\LINE: And for my means, I'll husband them so well,
\LINE: They shall go far with little.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Good Laertes,
\LINE: If you desire to know the certainty
\LINE: Of your dear father's death, is't writ in your revenge,
\LINE: That, swoopstake, you will draw both friend and foe,
\LINE: Winner and loser?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: None but his enemies.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Will you know them then?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: To his good friends thus wide I'll ope my arms;
\LINE: And like the kind life-rendering pelican,
\LINE: Repast them with my blood.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Why, now you speak
\LINE: Like a good child and a true gentleman.
\LINE: That I am guiltless of your father's death,
\LINE: And am most sensible in grief for it,
\LINE: It shall as level to your judgment pierce
\LINE: As day does to your eye.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Danes
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Within>                Let her come in.>
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: How now! what noise is that?
\STAGEDIR: Re-enter OPHELIA
\LINE: O heat, dry up my brains! tears seven times salt,
\LINE: Burn out the sense and virtue of mine eye!
\LINE: By heaven, thy madness shall be paid by weight,
\LINE: Till our scale turn the beam. O rose of May!
\LINE: Dear maid, kind sister, sweet Ophelia!
\LINE: O heavens! is't possible, a young maid's wits
\LINE: Should be as moral as an old man's life?
\LINE: Nature is fine in love, and where 'tis fine,
\LINE: It sends some precious instance of itself
\LINE: After the thing it loves.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Sings>>
\LINE: They bore him barefaced on the bier;
\LINE: Hey non nonny, nonny, hey nonny;
\LINE: And in his grave rain'd many a tear:--
\LINE: Fare you well, my dove!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Hadst thou thy wits, and didst persuade revenge,
\LINE: It could not move thus.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Sings>>
\LINE: You must sing a-down a-down,
\LINE: An you call him a-down-a.
\LINE: O, how the wheel becomes it! It is the false
\LINE: steward, that stole his master's daughter.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: This nothing's more than matter.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: There's rosemary, that's for remembrance; pray,
\LINE: love, remember: and there is pansies. that's for thoughts.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: A document in madness, thoughts and remembrance fitted.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE: There's fennel for you, and columbines: there's rue
\LINE: for you; and here's some for me: we may call it
\LINE: herb-grace o' Sundays: O you must wear your rue with
\LINE: a difference. There's a daisy: I would give you
\LINE: some violets, but they withered all when my father
\LINE: died: they say he made a good end,--
\STAGEDIR: Sings
\LINE: For bonny sweet Robin is all my joy.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Thought and affliction, passion, hell itself,
\LINE: She turns to favour and to prettiness.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OPHELIA
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Sings>>
\LINE: And will he not come again?
\LINE: And will he not come again?
\LINE: No, no, he is dead:
\LINE: Go to thy death-bed:
\LINE: He never will come again.
\LINE: His beard was as white as snow,
\LINE: All flaxen was his poll:
\LINE: He is gone, he is gone,
\LINE: And we cast away moan:
\LINE: God ha' mercy on his soul!
\LINE: And of all Christian souls, I pray God. God be wi' ye.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Do you see this, O God?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Laertes, I must commune with your grief,
\LINE: Or you deny me right. Go but apart,
\LINE: Make choice of whom your wisest friends you will.
\LINE: And they shall hear and judge 'twixt you and me:
\LINE: If by direct or by collateral hand
\LINE: They find us touch'd, we will our kingdom give,
\LINE: Our crown, our life, and all that we can ours,
\LINE: To you in satisfaction; but if not,
\LINE: Be you content to lend your patience to us,
\LINE: And we shall jointly labour with your soul
\LINE: To give it due content.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Let this be so;
\LINE: His means of death, his obscure funeral--
\LINE: No trophy, sword, nor hatchment o'er his bones,
\LINE: No noble rite nor formal ostentation--
\LINE: Cry to be heard, as 'twere from heaven to earth,
\LINE: That I must call't in question.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: So you shall;
\LINE: And where the offence is let the great axe fall.
\LINE: I pray you, go with me.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exeunt
>

\SCENE<\TITLE: SCENE VI.  Another room in the castle.
\STAGEDIR: Enter HORATIO and a Servant

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: What are they that would speak with me?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Servant
\LINE: Sailors, sir: they say they have letters for you.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Let them come in.
\STAGEDIR: Exit Servant
\LINE: I do not know from what part of the world
\LINE: I should be greeted, if not from Lord Hamlet.
>


\STAGEDIR: Enter Sailors

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Sailor
\LINE: God bless you, sir.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Let him bless thee too.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Sailor
\LINE: He shall, sir, an't please him. There's a letter for
\LINE: you, sir; it comes from the ambassador that was
\LINE: bound for England; if your name be Horatio, as I am
\LINE: let to know it is.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Reads>  'Horatio, when thou shalt have overlooked>
\LINE: this, give these fellows some means to the king:
\LINE: they have letters for him. Ere we were two days old
\LINE: at sea, a pirate of very warlike appointment gave us
\LINE: chase. Finding ourselves too slow of sail, we put on
\LINE: a compelled valour, and in the grapple I boarded
\LINE: them: on the instant they got clear of our ship; so
\LINE: I alone became their prisoner. They have dealt with
\LINE: me like thieves of mercy: but they knew what they
\LINE: did; I am to do a good turn for them. Let the king
\LINE: have the letters I have sent; and repair thou to me
\LINE: with as much speed as thou wouldst fly death. I
\LINE: have words to speak in thine ear will make thee
\LINE: dumb; yet are they much too light for the bore of
\LINE: the matter. These good fellows will bring thee
\LINE: where I am. Rosencrantz and Guildenstern hold their
\LINE: course for England: of them I have much to tell
\LINE: thee. Farewell.
\LINE: 'He that thou knowest thine, HAMLET.'
\LINE: Come, I will make you way for these your letters;
\LINE: And do't the speedier, that you may direct me
\LINE: To him from whom you brought them.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exeunt
>

\SCENE<\TITLE: SCENE VII.  Another room in the castle.
\STAGEDIR: Enter KING CLAUDIUS and LAERTES

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Now must your conscience my acquaintance seal,
\LINE: And you must put me in your heart for friend,
\LINE: Sith you have heard, and with a knowing ear,
\LINE: That he which hath your noble father slain
\LINE: Pursued my life.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: It well appears: but tell me
\LINE: Why you proceeded not against these feats,
\LINE: So crimeful and so capital in nature,
\LINE: As by your safety, wisdom, all things else,
\LINE: You mainly were stirr'd up.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: O, for two special reasons;
\LINE: Which may to you, perhaps, seem much unsinew'd,
\LINE: But yet to me they are strong. The queen his mother
\LINE: Lives almost by his looks; and for myself--
\LINE: My virtue or my plague, be it either which--
\LINE: She's so conjunctive to my life and soul,
\LINE: That, as the star moves not but in his sphere,
\LINE: I could not but by her. The other motive,
\LINE: Why to a public count I might not go,
\LINE: Is the great love the general gender bear him;
\LINE: Who, dipping all his faults in their affection,
\LINE: Would, like the spring that turneth wood to stone,
\LINE: Convert his gyves to graces; so that my arrows,
\LINE: Too slightly timber'd for so loud a wind,
\LINE: Would have reverted to my bow again,
\LINE: And not where I had aim'd them.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: And so have I a noble father lost;
\LINE: A sister driven into desperate terms,
\LINE: Whose worth, if praises may go back again,
\LINE: Stood challenger on mount of all the age
\LINE: For her perfections: but my revenge will come.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Break not your sleeps for that: you must not think
\LINE: That we are made of stuff so flat and dull
\LINE: That we can let our beard be shook with danger
\LINE: And think it pastime. You shortly shall hear more:
\LINE: I loved your father, and we love ourself;
\LINE: And that, I hope, will teach you to imagine--
\STAGEDIR: Enter a Messenger
\LINE: How now! what news?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Messenger
\LINE: Letters, my lord, from Hamlet:
\LINE: This to your majesty; this to the queen.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: From Hamlet! who brought them?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Messenger
\LINE: Sailors, my lord, they say; I saw them not:
\LINE: They were given me by Claudio; he received them
\LINE: Of him that brought them.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Laertes, you shall hear them. Leave us.
\STAGEDIR: Exit Messenger
\STAGEDIR: Reads
\LINE: 'High and mighty, You shall know I am set naked on
\LINE: your kingdom. To-morrow shall I beg leave to see
\LINE: your kingly eyes: when I shall, first asking your
\LINE: pardon thereunto, recount the occasion of my sudden
\LINE: and more strange return.                  'HAMLET.'
\LINE: What should this mean? Are all the rest come back?
\LINE: Or is it some abuse, and no such thing?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Know you the hand?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: 'Tis Hamlets character. 'Naked!
\LINE: And in a postscript here, he says 'alone.'
\LINE: Can you advise me?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: I'm lost in it, my lord. But let him come;
\LINE: It warms the very sickness in my heart,
\LINE: That I shall live and tell him to his teeth,
\LINE: 'Thus didest thou.'
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: If it be so, Laertes--
\LINE: As how should it be so? how otherwise?--
\LINE: Will you be ruled by me?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Ay, my lord;
\LINE: So you will not o'errule me to a peace.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: To thine own peace. If he be now return'd,
\LINE: As checking at his voyage, and that he means
\LINE: No more to undertake it, I will work him
\LINE: To an exploit, now ripe in my device,
\LINE: Under the which he shall not choose but fall:
\LINE: And for his death no wind of blame shall breathe,
\LINE: But even his mother shall uncharge the practise
\LINE: And call it accident.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: My lord, I will be ruled;
\LINE: The rather, if you could devise it so
\LINE: That I might be the organ.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: It falls right.
\LINE: You have been talk'd of since your travel much,
\LINE: And that in Hamlet's hearing, for a quality
\LINE: Wherein, they say, you shine: your sum of parts
\LINE: Did not together pluck such envy from him
\LINE: As did that one, and that, in my regard,
\LINE: Of the unworthiest siege.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: What part is that, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: A very riband in the cap of youth,
\LINE: Yet needful too; for youth no less becomes
\LINE: The light and careless livery that it wears
\LINE: Than settled age his sables and his weeds,
\LINE: Importing health and graveness. Two months since,
\LINE: Here was a gentleman of Normandy:--
\LINE: I've seen myself, and served against, the French,
\LINE: And they can well on horseback: but this gallant
\LINE: Had witchcraft in't; he grew unto his seat;
\LINE: And to such wondrous doing brought his horse,
\LINE: As he had been incorpsed and demi-natured
\LINE: With the brave beast: so far he topp'd my thought,
\LINE: That I, in forgery of shapes and tricks,
\LINE: Come short of what he did.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: A Norman was't?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: A Norman.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Upon my life, Lamond.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: The very same.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: I know him well: he is the brooch indeed
\LINE: And gem of all the nation.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: He made confession of you,
\LINE: And gave you such a masterly report
\LINE: For art and exercise in your defence
\LINE: And for your rapier most especially,
\LINE: That he cried out, 'twould be a sight indeed,
\LINE: If one could match you: the scrimers of their nation,
\LINE: He swore, had had neither motion, guard, nor eye,
\LINE: If you opposed them. Sir, this report of his
\LINE: Did Hamlet so envenom with his envy
\LINE: That he could nothing do but wish and beg
\LINE: Your sudden coming o'er, to play with him.
\LINE: Now, out of this,--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: What out of this, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Laertes, was your father dear to you?
\LINE: Or are you like the painting of a sorrow,
\LINE: A face without a heart?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Why ask you this?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Not that I think you did not love your father;
\LINE: But that I know love is begun by time;
\LINE: And that I see, in passages of proof,
\LINE: Time qualifies the spark and fire of it.
\LINE: There lives within the very flame of love
\LINE: A kind of wick or snuff that will abate it;
\LINE: And nothing is at a like goodness still;
\LINE: For goodness, growing to a plurisy,
\LINE: Dies in his own too much: that we would do
\LINE: We should do when we would; for this 'would' changes
\LINE: And hath abatements and delays as many
\LINE: As there are tongues, are hands, are accidents;
\LINE: And then this 'should' is like a spendthrift sigh,
\LINE: That hurts by easing. But, to the quick o' the ulcer:--
\LINE: Hamlet comes back: what would you undertake,
\LINE: To show yourself your father's son in deed
\LINE: More than in words?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: To cut his throat i' the church.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: No place, indeed, should murder sanctuarize;
\LINE: Revenge should have no bounds. But, good Laertes,
\LINE: Will you do this, keep close within your chamber.
\LINE: Hamlet return'd shall know you are come home:
\LINE: We'll put on those shall praise your excellence
\LINE: And set a double varnish on the fame
\LINE: The Frenchman gave you, bring you in fine together
\LINE: And wager on your heads: he, being remiss,
\LINE: Most generous and free from all contriving,
\LINE: Will not peruse the foils; so that, with ease,
\LINE: Or with a little shuffling, you may choose
\LINE: A sword unbated, and in a pass of practise
\LINE: Requite him for your father.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: I will do't:
\LINE: And, for that purpose, I'll anoint my sword.
\LINE: I bought an unction of a mountebank,
\LINE: So mortal that, but dip a knife in it,
\LINE: Where it draws blood no cataplasm so rare,
\LINE: Collected from all simples that have virtue
\LINE: Under the moon, can save the thing from death
\LINE: That is but scratch'd withal: I'll touch my point
\LINE: With this contagion, that, if I gall him slightly,
\LINE: It may be death.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Let's further think of this;
\LINE: Weigh what convenience both of time and means
\LINE: May fit us to our shape: if this should fail,
\LINE: And that our drift look through our bad performance,
\LINE: 'Twere better not assay'd: therefore this project
\LINE: Should have a back or second, that might hold,
\LINE: If this should blast in proof. Soft! let me see:
\LINE: We'll make a solemn wager on your cunnings: I ha't.
\LINE: When in your motion you are hot and dry--
\LINE: As make your bouts more violent to that end--
\LINE: And that he calls for drink, I'll have prepared him
\LINE: A chalice for the nonce, whereon but sipping,
\LINE: If he by chance escape your venom'd stuck,
\LINE: Our purpose may hold there.
\STAGEDIR: Enter QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: How now, sweet queen!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: One woe doth tread upon another's heel,
\LINE: So fast they follow; your sister's drown'd, Laertes.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Drown'd! O, where?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: There is a willow grows aslant a brook,
\LINE: That shows his hoar leaves in the glassy stream;
\LINE: There with fantastic garlands did she come
\LINE: Of crow-flowers, nettles, daisies, and long purples
\LINE: That liberal shepherds give a grosser name,
\LINE: But our cold maids do dead men's fingers call them:
\LINE: There, on the pendent boughs her coronet weeds
\LINE: Clambering to hang, an envious sliver broke;
\LINE: When down her weedy trophies and herself
\LINE: Fell in the weeping brook. Her clothes spread wide;
\LINE: And, mermaid-like, awhile they bore her up:
\LINE: Which time she chanted snatches of old tunes;
\LINE: As one incapable of her own distress,
\LINE: Or like a creature native and indued
\LINE: Unto that element: but long it could not be
\LINE: Till that her garments, heavy with their drink,
\LINE: Pull'd the poor wretch from her melodious lay
\LINE: To muddy death.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Alas, then, she is drown'd?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Drown'd, drown'd.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Too much of water hast thou, poor Ophelia,
\LINE: And therefore I forbid my tears: but yet
\LINE: It is our trick; nature her custom holds,
\LINE: Let shame say what it will: when these are gone,
\LINE: The woman will be out. Adieu, my lord:
\LINE: I have a speech of fire, that fain would blaze,
\LINE: But that this folly douts it.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Let's follow, Gertrude:
\LINE: How much I had to do to calm his rage!
\LINE: Now fear I this will give it start again;
\LINE: Therefore let's follow.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exeunt
>

>

\ACT<\TITLE: ACT V

\SCENE<\TITLE: SCENE I.  A churchyard.
\STAGEDIR: Enter two Clowns, with spades, &amp;c

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: Is she to be buried in Christian burial that
\LINE: wilfully seeks her own salvation?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Second Clown
\LINE: I tell thee she is: and therefore make her grave
\LINE: straight: the crowner hath sat on her, and finds it
\LINE: Christian burial.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: How can that be, unless she drowned herself in her
\LINE: own defence?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Second Clown
\LINE: Why, 'tis found so.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: It must be 'se offendendo;' it cannot be else. For
\LINE: here lies the point:  if I drown myself wittingly,
\LINE: it argues an act: and an act hath three branches: it
\LINE: is, to act, to do, to perform: argal, she drowned
\LINE: herself wittingly.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Second Clown
\LINE: Nay, but hear you, goodman delver,--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: Give me leave. Here lies the water; good: here
\LINE: stands the man; good; if the man go to this water,
\LINE: and drown himself, it is, will he, nill he, he
\LINE: goes,--mark you that; but if the water come to him
\LINE: and drown him, he drowns not himself: argal, he
\LINE: that is not guilty of his own death shortens not his own life.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Second Clown
\LINE: But is this law?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: Ay, marry, is't; crowner's quest law.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Second Clown
\LINE: Will you ha' the truth on't? If this had not been
\LINE: a gentlewoman, she should have been buried out o'
\LINE: Christian burial.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: Why, there thou say'st: and the more pity that
\LINE: great folk should have countenance in this world to
\LINE: drown or hang themselves, more than their even
\LINE: Christian. Come, my spade. There is no ancient
\LINE: gentleman but gardeners, ditchers, and grave-makers:
\LINE: they hold up Adam's profession.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Second Clown
\LINE: Was he a gentleman?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: He was the first that ever bore arms.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Second Clown
\LINE: Why, he had none.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: What, art a heathen? How dost thou understand the
\LINE: Scripture? The Scripture says 'Adam digged:'
\LINE: could he dig without arms? I'll put another
\LINE: question to thee: if thou answerest me not to the
\LINE: purpose, confess thyself--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Second Clown
\LINE: Go to.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: What is he that builds stronger than either the
\LINE: mason, the shipwright, or the carpenter?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Second Clown
\LINE: The gallows-maker; for that frame outlives a
\LINE: thousand tenants.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: I like thy wit well, in good faith: the gallows
\LINE: does well; but how does it well? it does well to
\LINE: those that do in: now thou dost ill to say the
\LINE: gallows is built stronger than the church: argal,
\LINE: the gallows may do well to thee. To't again, come.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Second Clown
\LINE: 'Who builds stronger than a mason, a shipwright, or
\LINE: a carpenter?'
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: Ay, tell me that, and unyoke.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Second Clown
\LINE: Marry, now I can tell.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: To't.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Second Clown
\LINE: Mass, I cannot tell.
>


\STAGEDIR: Enter HAMLET and HORATIO, at a distance

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: Cudgel thy brains no more about it, for your dull
\LINE: ass will not mend his pace with beating; and, when
\LINE: you are asked this question next, say 'a
\LINE: grave-maker: 'the houses that he makes last till
\LINE: doomsday. Go, get thee to Yaughan: fetch me a
\LINE: stoup of liquor.
\STAGEDIR: Exit Second Clown
\STAGEDIR: He digs and sings
\LINE: In youth, when I did love, did love,
\LINE: Methought it was very sweet,
\LINE: To contract, O, the time, for, ah, my behove,
\LINE: O, methought, there was nothing meet.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Has this fellow no feeling of his business, that he
\LINE: sings at grave-making?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Custom hath made it in him a property of easiness.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: 'Tis e'en so: the hand of little employment hath
\LINE: the daintier sense.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Sings>>
\LINE: But age, with his stealing steps,
\LINE: Hath claw'd me in his clutch,
\LINE: And hath shipped me intil the land,
\LINE: As if I had never been such.
>


\STAGEDIR: Throws up a skull

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: That skull had a tongue in it, and could sing once:
\LINE: how the knave jowls it to the ground, as if it were
\LINE: Cain's jaw-bone, that did the first murder! It
\LINE: might be the pate of a politician, which this ass
\LINE: now o'er-reaches; one that would circumvent God,
\LINE: might it not?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: It might, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Or of a courtier; which could say 'Good morrow,
\LINE: sweet lord! How dost thou, good lord?' This might
\LINE: be my lord such-a-one, that praised my lord
\LINE: such-a-one's horse, when he meant to beg it; might it not?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Ay, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Why, e'en so: and now my Lady Worm's; chapless, and
\LINE: knocked about the mazzard with a sexton's spade:
\LINE: here's fine revolution, an we had the trick to
\LINE: see't. Did these bones cost no more the breeding,
\LINE: but to play at loggats with 'em? mine ache to think on't.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\STAGEDIR: Sings
\LINE: A pick-axe, and a spade, a spade,
\LINE: For and a shrouding sheet:
\LINE: O, a pit of clay for to be made
\LINE: For such a guest is meet.
>


\STAGEDIR: Throws up another skull

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: There's another: why may not that be the skull of a
\LINE: lawyer? Where be his quiddities now, his quillets,
\LINE: his cases, his tenures, and his tricks? why does he
\LINE: suffer this rude knave now to knock him about the
\LINE: sconce with a dirty shovel, and will not tell him of
\LINE: his action of battery? Hum! This fellow might be
\LINE: in's time a great buyer of land, with his statutes,
\LINE: his recognizances, his fines, his double vouchers,
\LINE: his recoveries: is this the fine of his fines, and
\LINE: the recovery of his recoveries, to have his fine
\LINE: pate full of fine dirt? will his vouchers vouch him
\LINE: no more of his purchases, and double ones too, than
\LINE: the length and breadth of a pair of indentures? The
\LINE: very conveyances of his lands will hardly lie in
\LINE: this box; and must the inheritor himself have no more, ha?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Not a jot more, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Is not parchment made of sheepskins?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Ay, my lord, and of calf-skins too.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: They are sheep and calves which seek out assurance
\LINE: in that. I will speak to this fellow. Whose
\LINE: grave's this, sirrah?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: Mine, sir.
\STAGEDIR: Sings
\LINE: O, a pit of clay for to be made
\LINE: For such a guest is meet.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I think it be thine, indeed; for thou liest in't.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: You lie out on't, sir, and therefore it is not
\LINE: yours: for my part, I do not lie in't, and yet it is mine.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: 'Thou dost lie in't, to be in't and say it is thine:
\LINE: 'tis for the dead, not for the quick; therefore thou liest.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: 'Tis a quick lie, sir; 'twill away gain, from me to
\LINE: you.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: What man dost thou dig it for?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: For no man, sir.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: What woman, then?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: For none, neither.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Who is to be buried in't?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: One that was a woman, sir; but, rest her soul, she's dead.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: How absolute the knave is! we must speak by the
\LINE: card, or equivocation will undo us. By the Lord,
\LINE: Horatio, these three years I have taken a note of
\LINE: it; the age is grown so picked that the toe of the
\LINE: peasant comes so near the heel of the courtier, he
\LINE: gaffs his kibe. How long hast thou been a
\LINE: grave-maker?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: Of all the days i' the year, I came to't that day
\LINE: that our last king Hamlet overcame Fortinbras.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: How long is that since?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: Cannot you tell that? every fool can tell that: it
\LINE: was the very day that young Hamlet was born; he that
\LINE: is mad, and sent into England.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Ay, marry, why was he sent into England?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: Why, because he was mad: he shall recover his wits
\LINE: there; or, if he do not, it's no great matter there.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Why?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: 'Twill, a not be seen in him there; there the men
\LINE: are as mad as he.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: How came he mad?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: Very strangely, they say.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: How strangely?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: Faith, e'en with losing his wits.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Upon what ground?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: Why, here in Denmark: I have been sexton here, man
\LINE: and boy, thirty years.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: How long will a man lie i' the earth ere he rot?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: I' faith, if he be not rotten before he die--as we
\LINE: have many pocky corses now-a-days, that will scarce
\LINE: hold the laying in--he will last you some eight year
\LINE: or nine year: a tanner will last you nine year.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Why he more than another?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: Why, sir, his hide is so tanned with his trade, that
\LINE: he will keep out water a great while; and your water
\LINE: is a sore decayer of your whoreson dead body.
\LINE: Here's a skull now; this skull has lain in the earth
\LINE: three and twenty years.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Whose was it?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: A whoreson mad fellow's it was: whose do you think it was?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Nay, I know not.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: A pestilence on him for a mad rogue! a' poured a
\LINE: flagon of Rhenish on my head once. This same skull,
\LINE: sir, was Yorick's skull, the king's jester.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: This?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Clown
\LINE: E'en that.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Let me see.
\STAGEDIR: Takes the skull
\LINE: Alas, poor Yorick! I knew him, Horatio: a fellow
\LINE: of infinite jest, of most excellent fancy: he hath
\LINE: borne me on his back a thousand times; and now, how
\LINE: abhorred in my imagination it is! my gorge rims at
\LINE: it. Here hung those lips that I have kissed I know
\LINE: not how oft. Where be your gibes now? your
\LINE: gambols? your songs? your flashes of merriment,
\LINE: that were wont to set the table on a roar? Not one
\LINE: now, to mock your own grinning? quite chap-fallen?
\LINE: Now get you to my lady's chamber, and tell her, let
\LINE: her paint an inch thick, to this favour she must
\LINE: come; make her laugh at that. Prithee, Horatio, tell
\LINE: me one thing.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: What's that, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Dost thou think Alexander looked o' this fashion i'
\LINE: the earth?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: E'en so.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: And smelt so? pah!
>


\STAGEDIR: Puts down the skull

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: E'en so, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: To what base uses we may return, Horatio! Why may
\LINE: not imagination trace the noble dust of Alexander,
\LINE: till he find it stopping a bung-hole?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: 'Twere to consider too curiously, to consider so.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: No, faith, not a jot; but to follow him thither with
\LINE: modesty enough, and likelihood to lead it: as
\LINE: thus: Alexander died, Alexander was buried,
\LINE: Alexander returneth into dust; the dust is earth; of
\LINE: earth we make loam; and why of that loam, whereto he
\LINE: was converted, might they not stop a beer-barrel?
\LINE: Imperious Caesar, dead and turn'd to clay,
\LINE: Might stop a hole to keep the wind away:
\LINE: O, that that earth, which kept the world in awe,
\LINE: Should patch a wall to expel the winter flaw!
\LINE: But soft! but soft! aside: here comes the king.
\STAGEDIR<Enter Priest, &amp;c. in procession; the Corpse of
OPHELIA, LAERTES and Mourners following; KING
CLAUDIUS, QUEEN GERTRUDE, their trains, &amp;c>
\LINE: The queen, the courtiers: who is this they follow?
\LINE: And with such maimed rites? This doth betoken
\LINE: The corse they follow did with desperate hand
\LINE: Fordo its own life: 'twas of some estate.
\LINE: Couch we awhile, and mark.
>


\STAGEDIR: Retiring with HORATIO

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: What ceremony else?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: That is Laertes,
\LINE: A very noble youth: mark.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: What ceremony else?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Priest
\LINE: Her obsequies have been as far enlarged
\LINE: As we have warrantise: her death was doubtful;
\LINE: And, but that great command o'ersways the order,
\LINE: She should in ground unsanctified have lodged
\LINE: Till the last trumpet: for charitable prayers,
\LINE: Shards, flints and pebbles should be thrown on her;
\LINE: Yet here she is allow'd her virgin crants,
\LINE: Her maiden strewments and the bringing home
\LINE: Of bell and burial.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Must there no more be done?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Priest
\LINE: No more be done:
\LINE: We should profane the service of the dead
\LINE: To sing a requiem and such rest to her
\LINE: As to peace-parted souls.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Lay her i' the earth:
\LINE: And from her fair and unpolluted flesh
\LINE: May violets spring! I tell thee, churlish priest,
\LINE: A ministering angel shall my sister be,
\LINE: When thou liest howling.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: What, the fair Ophelia!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Sweets to the sweet: farewell!
\STAGEDIR: Scattering flowers
\LINE: I hoped thou shouldst have been my Hamlet's wife;
\LINE: I thought thy bride-bed to have deck'd, sweet maid,
\LINE: And not have strew'd thy grave.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: O, treble woe
\LINE: Fall ten times treble on that cursed head,
\LINE: Whose wicked deed thy most ingenious sense
\LINE: Deprived thee of! Hold off the earth awhile,
\LINE: Till I have caught her once more in mine arms:
\STAGEDIR: Leaps into the grave
\LINE: Now pile your dust upon the quick and dead,
\LINE: Till of this flat a mountain you have made,
\LINE: To o'ertop old Pelion, or the skyish head
\LINE: Of blue Olympus.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Advancing>     What is he whose grief>
\LINE: Bears such an emphasis? whose phrase of sorrow
\LINE: Conjures the wandering stars, and makes them stand
\LINE: Like wonder-wounded hearers? This is I,
\LINE: Hamlet the Dane.
>


\STAGEDIR: Leaps into the grave

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: The devil take thy soul!
>


\STAGEDIR: Grappling with him

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Thou pray'st not well.
\LINE: I prithee, take thy fingers from my throat;
\LINE: For, though I am not splenitive and rash,
\LINE: Yet have I something in me dangerous,
\LINE: Which let thy wiseness fear: hold off thy hand.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Pluck them asunder.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Hamlet, Hamlet!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: All
\LINE: Gentlemen,--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Good my lord, be quiet.
>


\STAGEDIR: The Attendants part them, and they come out of the grave

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Why I will fight with him upon this theme
\LINE: Until my eyelids will no longer wag.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: O my son, what theme?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I loved Ophelia: forty thousand brothers
\LINE: Could not, with all their quantity of love,
\LINE: Make up my sum. What wilt thou do for her?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: O, he is mad, Laertes.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: For love of God, forbear him.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: 'Swounds, show me what thou'lt do:
\LINE: Woo't weep? woo't fight? woo't fast? woo't tear thyself?
\LINE: Woo't drink up eisel? eat a crocodile?
\LINE: I'll do't. Dost thou come here to whine?
\LINE: To outface me with leaping in her grave?
\LINE: Be buried quick with her, and so will I:
\LINE: And, if thou prate of mountains, let them throw
\LINE: Millions of acres on us, till our ground,
\LINE: Singeing his pate against the burning zone,
\LINE: Make Ossa like a wart! Nay, an thou'lt mouth,
\LINE: I'll rant as well as thou.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: This is mere madness:
\LINE: And thus awhile the fit will work on him;
\LINE: Anon, as patient as the female dove,
\LINE: When that her golden couplets are disclosed,
\LINE: His silence will sit drooping.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Hear you, sir;
\LINE: What is the reason that you use me thus?
\LINE: I loved you ever: but it is no matter;
\LINE: Let Hercules himself do what he may,
\LINE: The cat will mew and dog will have his day.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: I pray you, good Horatio, wait upon him.
\STAGEDIR: Exit HORATIO
\STAGEDIR: To LAERTES
\LINE: Strengthen your patience in our last night's speech;
\LINE: We'll put the matter to the present push.
\LINE: Good Gertrude, set some watch over your son.
\LINE: This grave shall have a living monument:
\LINE: An hour of quiet shortly shall we see;
\LINE: Till then, in patience our proceeding be.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exeunt
>

\SCENE<\TITLE: SCENE II.  A hall in the castle.
\STAGEDIR: Enter HAMLET and HORATIO

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: So much for this, sir: now shall you see the other;
\LINE: You do remember all the circumstance?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Remember it, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Sir, in my heart there was a kind of fighting,
\LINE: That would not let me sleep: methought I lay
\LINE: Worse than the mutines in the bilboes. Rashly,
\LINE: And praised be rashness for it, let us know,
\LINE: Our indiscretion sometimes serves us well,
\LINE: When our deep plots do pall: and that should teach us
\LINE: There's a divinity that shapes our ends,
\LINE: Rough-hew them how we will,--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: That is most certain.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Up from my cabin,
\LINE: My sea-gown scarf'd about me, in the dark
\LINE: Groped I to find out them; had my desire.
\LINE: Finger'd their packet, and in fine withdrew
\LINE: To mine own room again; making so bold,
\LINE: My fears forgetting manners, to unseal
\LINE: Their grand commission; where I found, Horatio,--
\LINE: O royal knavery!--an exact command,
\LINE: Larded with many several sorts of reasons
\LINE: Importing Denmark's health and England's too,
\LINE: With, ho! such bugs and goblins in my life,
\LINE: That, on the supervise, no leisure bated,
\LINE: No, not to stay the grinding of the axe,
\LINE: My head should be struck off.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Is't possible?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Here's the commission: read it at more leisure.
\LINE: But wilt thou hear me how I did proceed?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: I beseech you.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Being thus be-netted round with villanies,--
\LINE: Ere I could make a prologue to my brains,
\LINE: They had begun the play--I sat me down,
\LINE: Devised a new commission, wrote it fair:
\LINE: I once did hold it, as our statists do,
\LINE: A baseness to write fair and labour'd much
\LINE: How to forget that learning, but, sir, now
\LINE: It did me yeoman's service: wilt thou know
\LINE: The effect of what I wrote?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Ay, good my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: An earnest conjuration from the king,
\LINE: As England was his faithful tributary,
\LINE: As love between them like the palm might flourish,
\LINE: As peace should stiff her wheaten garland wear
\LINE: And stand a comma 'tween their amities,
\LINE: And many such-like 'As'es of great charge,
\LINE: That, on the view and knowing of these contents,
\LINE: Without debatement further, more or less,
\LINE: He should the bearers put to sudden death,
\LINE: Not shriving-time allow'd.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: How was this seal'd?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Why, even in that was heaven ordinant.
\LINE: I had my father's signet in my purse,
\LINE: Which was the model of that Danish seal;
\LINE: Folded the writ up in form of the other,
\LINE: Subscribed it, gave't the impression, placed it safely,
\LINE: The changeling never known. Now, the next day
\LINE: Was our sea-fight; and what to this was sequent
\LINE: Thou know'st already.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: So Guildenstern and Rosencrantz go to't.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Why, man, they did make love to this employment;
\LINE: They are not near my conscience; their defeat
\LINE: Does by their own insinuation grow:
\LINE: 'Tis dangerous when the baser nature comes
\LINE: Between the pass and fell incensed points
\LINE: Of mighty opposites.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Why, what a king is this!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Does it not, think'st thee, stand me now upon--
\LINE: He that hath kill'd my king and whored my mother,
\LINE: Popp'd in between the election and my hopes,
\LINE: Thrown out his angle for my proper life,
\LINE: And with such cozenage--is't not perfect conscience,
\LINE: To quit him with this arm? and is't not to be damn'd,
\LINE: To let this canker of our nature come
\LINE: In further evil?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: It must be shortly known to him from England
\LINE: What is the issue of the business there.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: It will be short: the interim is mine;
\LINE: And a man's life's no more than to say 'One.'
\LINE: But I am very sorry, good Horatio,
\LINE: That to Laertes I forgot myself;
\LINE: For, by the image of my cause, I see
\LINE: The portraiture of his: I'll court his favours.
\LINE: But, sure, the bravery of his grief did put me
\LINE: Into a towering passion.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Peace! who comes here?
>


\STAGEDIR: Enter OSRIC

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: Your lordship is right welcome back to Denmark.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I humbly thank you, sir. Dost know this water-fly?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: No, my good lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Thy state is the more gracious; for 'tis a vice to
\LINE: know him. He hath much land, and fertile: let a
\LINE: beast be lord of beasts, and his crib shall stand at
\LINE: the king's mess: 'tis a chough; but, as I say,
\LINE: spacious in the possession of dirt.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: Sweet lord, if your lordship were at leisure, I
\LINE: should impart a thing to you from his majesty.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I will receive it, sir, with all diligence of
\LINE: spirit. Put your bonnet to his right use; 'tis for the head.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: I thank your lordship, it is very hot.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: No, believe me, 'tis very cold; the wind is
\LINE: northerly.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: It is indifferent cold, my lord, indeed.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: But yet methinks it is very sultry and hot for my
\LINE: complexion.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: Exceedingly, my lord; it is very sultry,--as
\LINE: 'twere,--I cannot tell how. But, my lord, his
\LINE: majesty bade me signify to you that he has laid a
\LINE: great wager on your head: sir, this is the matter,--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I beseech you, remember--
>


\STAGEDIR: HAMLET moves him to put on his hat

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: Nay, good my lord; for mine ease, in good faith.
\LINE: Sir, here is newly come to court Laertes; believe
\LINE: me, an absolute gentleman, full of most excellent
\LINE: differences, of very soft society and great showing:
\LINE: indeed, to speak feelingly of him, he is the card or
\LINE: calendar of gentry, for you shall find in him the
\LINE: continent of what part a gentleman would see.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Sir, his definement suffers no perdition in you;
\LINE: though, I know, to divide him inventorially would
\LINE: dizzy the arithmetic of memory, and yet but yaw
\LINE: neither, in respect of his quick sail. But, in the
\LINE: verity of extolment, I take him to be a soul of
\LINE: great article; and his infusion of such dearth and
\LINE: rareness, as, to make true diction of him, his
\LINE: semblable is his mirror; and who else would trace
\LINE: him, his umbrage, nothing more.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: Your lordship speaks most infallibly of him.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: The concernancy, sir? why do we wrap the gentleman
\LINE: in our more rawer breath?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: Sir?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Is't not possible to understand in another tongue?
\LINE: You will do't, sir, really.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: What imports the nomination of this gentleman?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: Of Laertes?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: His purse is empty already; all's golden words are spent.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Of him, sir.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: I know you are not ignorant--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I would you did, sir; yet, in faith, if you did,
\LINE: it would not much approve me. Well, sir?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: You are not ignorant of what excellence Laertes is--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I dare not confess that, lest I should compare with
\LINE: him in excellence; but, to know a man well, were to
\LINE: know himself.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: I mean, sir, for his weapon; but in the imputation
\LINE: laid on him by them, in his meed he's unfellowed.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: What's his weapon?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: Rapier and dagger.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: That's two of his weapons: but, well.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: The king, sir, hath wagered with him six Barbary
\LINE: horses: against the which he has imponed, as I take
\LINE: it, six French rapiers and poniards, with their
\LINE: assigns, as girdle, hangers, and so: three of the
\LINE: carriages, in faith, are very dear to fancy, very
\LINE: responsive to the hilts, most delicate carriages,
\LINE: and of very liberal conceit.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: What call you the carriages?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: I knew you must be edified by the margent ere you had done.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: The carriages, sir, are the hangers.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: The phrase would be more german to the matter, if we
\LINE: could carry cannon by our sides: I would it might
\LINE: be hangers till then. But, on: six Barbary horses
\LINE: against six French swords, their assigns, and three
\LINE: liberal-conceited carriages; that's the French bet
\LINE: against the Danish. Why is this 'imponed,' as you call it?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: The king, sir, hath laid, that in a dozen passes
\LINE: between yourself and him, he shall not exceed you
\LINE: three hits: he hath laid on twelve for nine; and it
\LINE: would come to immediate trial, if your lordship
\LINE: would vouchsafe the answer.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: How if I answer 'no'?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: I mean, my lord, the opposition of your person in trial.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Sir, I will walk here in the hall: if it please his
\LINE: majesty, 'tis the breathing time of day with me; let
\LINE: the foils be brought, the gentleman willing, and the
\LINE: king hold his purpose, I will win for him an I can;
\LINE: if not, I will gain nothing but my shame and the odd hits.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: Shall I re-deliver you e'en so?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: To this effect, sir; after what flourish your nature will.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: I commend my duty to your lordship.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Yours, yours.
\STAGEDIR: Exit OSRIC
\LINE: He does well to commend it himself; there are no
\LINE: tongues else for's turn.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: This lapwing runs away with the shell on his head.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: He did comply with his dug, before he sucked it.
\LINE: Thus has he--and many more of the same bevy that I
\LINE: know the dressy age dotes on--only got the tune of
\LINE: the time and outward habit of encounter; a kind of
\LINE: yesty collection, which carries them through and
\LINE: through the most fond and winnowed opinions; and do
\LINE: but blow them to their trial, the bubbles are out.
>


\STAGEDIR: Enter a Lord

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Lord
\LINE: My lord, his majesty commended him to you by young
\LINE: Osric, who brings back to him that you attend him in
\LINE: the hall: he sends to know if your pleasure hold to
\LINE: play with Laertes, or that you will take longer time.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I am constant to my purpose; they follow the king's
\LINE: pleasure: if his fitness speaks, mine is ready; now
\LINE: or whensoever, provided I be so able as now.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Lord
\LINE: The king and queen and all are coming down.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: In happy time.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: Lord
\LINE: The queen desires you to use some gentle
\LINE: entertainment to Laertes before you fall to play.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: She well instructs me.
>


\STAGEDIR: Exit Lord

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: You will lose this wager, my lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I do not think so: since he went into France, I
\LINE: have been in continual practise: I shall win at the
\LINE: odds. But thou wouldst not think how ill all's here
\LINE: about my heart: but it is no matter.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Nay, good my lord,--
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: It is but foolery; but it is such a kind of
\LINE: gain-giving, as would perhaps trouble a woman.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: If your mind dislike any thing, obey it: I will
\LINE: forestall their repair hither, and say you are not
\LINE: fit.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Not a whit, we defy augury: there's a special
\LINE: providence in the fall of a sparrow. If it be now,
\LINE: 'tis not to come; if it be not to come, it will be
\LINE: now; if it be not now, yet it will come: the
\LINE: readiness is all: since no man has aught of what he
\LINE: leaves, what is't to leave betimes?
>


\STAGEDIR<Enter KING CLAUDIUS, QUEEN GERTRUDE, LAERTES,
Lords, OSRIC, and Attendants with foils, &amp;c>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Come, Hamlet, come, and take this hand from me.
>


\STAGEDIR: KING CLAUDIUS puts LAERTES' hand into HAMLET's

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Give me your pardon, sir: I've done you wrong;
\LINE: But pardon't, as you are a gentleman.
\LINE: This presence knows,
\LINE: And you must needs have heard, how I am punish'd
\LINE: With sore distraction. What I have done,
\LINE: That might your nature, honour and exception
\LINE: Roughly awake, I here proclaim was madness.
\LINE: Was't Hamlet wrong'd Laertes? Never Hamlet:
\LINE: If Hamlet from himself be ta'en away,
\LINE: And when he's not himself does wrong Laertes,
\LINE: Then Hamlet does it not, Hamlet denies it.
\LINE: Who does it, then? His madness: if't be so,
\LINE: Hamlet is of the faction that is wrong'd;
\LINE: His madness is poor Hamlet's enemy.
\LINE: Sir, in this audience,
\LINE: Let my disclaiming from a purposed evil
\LINE: Free me so far in your most generous thoughts,
\LINE: That I have shot mine arrow o'er the house,
\LINE: And hurt my brother.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: I am satisfied in nature,
\LINE: Whose motive, in this case, should stir me most
\LINE: To my revenge: but in my terms of honour
\LINE: I stand aloof; and will no reconcilement,
\LINE: Till by some elder masters, of known honour,
\LINE: I have a voice and precedent of peace,
\LINE: To keep my name ungored. But till that time,
\LINE: I do receive your offer'd love like love,
\LINE: And will not wrong it.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I embrace it freely;
\LINE: And will this brother's wager frankly play.
\LINE: Give us the foils. Come on.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Come, one for me.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I'll be your foil, Laertes: in mine ignorance
\LINE: Your skill shall, like a star i' the darkest night,
\LINE: Stick fiery off indeed.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: You mock me, sir.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: No, by this hand.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Give them the foils, young Osric. Cousin Hamlet,
\LINE: You know the wager?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Very well, my lord
\LINE: Your grace hath laid the odds o' the weaker side.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: I do not fear it; I have seen you both:
\LINE: But since he is better'd, we have therefore odds.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: This is too heavy, let me see another.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: This likes me well. These foils have all a length?
>


\STAGEDIR: They prepare to play

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: Ay, my good lord.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Set me the stoops of wine upon that table.
\LINE: If Hamlet give the first or second hit,
\LINE: Or quit in answer of the third exchange,
\LINE: Let all the battlements their ordnance fire:
\LINE: The king shall drink to Hamlet's better breath;
\LINE: And in the cup an union shall he throw,
\LINE: Richer than that which four successive kings
\LINE: In Denmark's crown have worn. Give me the cups;
\LINE: And let the kettle to the trumpet speak,
\LINE: The trumpet to the cannoneer without,
\LINE: The cannons to the heavens, the heavens to earth,
\LINE: 'Now the king dunks to Hamlet.' Come, begin:
\LINE: And you, the judges, bear a wary eye.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Come on, sir.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Come, my lord.
>


\STAGEDIR: They play

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: One.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: No.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Judgment.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: A hit, a very palpable hit.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Well; again.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Stay; give me drink. Hamlet, this pearl is thine;
\LINE: Here's to thy health.
\STAGEDIR: Trumpets sound, and cannon shot off within
\LINE: Give him the cup.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I'll play this bout first; set it by awhile. Come.
\STAGEDIR: They play
\LINE: Another hit; what say you?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: A touch, a touch, I do confess.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Our son shall win.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: He's fat, and scant of breath.
\LINE: Here, Hamlet, take my napkin, rub thy brows;
\LINE: The queen carouses to thy fortune, Hamlet.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Good madam!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Gertrude, do not drink.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: I will, my lord; I pray you, pardon me.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Aside>  It is the poison'd cup: it is too late.>
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: I dare not drink yet, madam; by and by.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: Come, let me wipe thy face.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: My lord, I'll hit him now.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: I do not think't.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE<\STAGEDIR<Aside>  And yet 'tis almost 'gainst my conscience.>
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Come, for the third, Laertes: you but dally;
\LINE: I pray you, pass with your best violence;
\LINE: I am afeard you make a wanton of me.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Say you so? come on.
>


\STAGEDIR: They play

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: Nothing, neither way.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Have at you now!
>


\STAGEDIR<LAERTES wounds HAMLET; then in scuffling, they
change rapiers, and HAMLET wounds LAERTES>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: Part them; they are incensed.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Nay, come, again.
>


\STAGEDIR: QUEEN GERTRUDE falls

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: Look to the queen there, ho!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: They bleed on both sides. How is it, my lord?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: How is't, Laertes?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: Why, as a woodcock to mine own springe, Osric;
\LINE: I am justly kill'd with mine own treachery.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: How does the queen?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: She swounds to see them bleed.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: QUEEN GERTRUDE
\LINE: No, no, the drink, the drink,--O my dear Hamlet,--
\LINE: The drink, the drink! I am poison'd.
>


\STAGEDIR: Dies

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: O villany! Ho! let the door be lock'd:
\LINE: Treachery! Seek it out.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: It is here, Hamlet: Hamlet, thou art slain;
\LINE: No medicine in the world can do thee good;
\LINE: In thee there is not half an hour of life;
\LINE: The treacherous instrument is in thy hand,
\LINE: Unbated and envenom'd: the foul practise
\LINE: Hath turn'd itself on me lo, here I lie,
\LINE: Never to rise again: thy mother's poison'd:
\LINE: I can no more: the king, the king's to blame.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: The point!--envenom'd too!
\LINE: Then, venom, to thy work.
>


\STAGEDIR: Stabs KING CLAUDIUS

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: All
\LINE: Treason! treason!
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: KING CLAUDIUS
\LINE: O, yet defend me, friends; I am but hurt.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Here, thou incestuous, murderous, damned Dane,
\LINE: Drink off this potion. Is thy union here?
\LINE: Follow my mother.
>


\STAGEDIR: KING CLAUDIUS dies

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: LAERTES
\LINE: He is justly served;
\LINE: It is a poison temper'd by himself.
\LINE: Exchange forgiveness with me, noble Hamlet:
\LINE: Mine and my father's death come not upon thee,
\LINE: Nor thine on me.
>


\STAGEDIR: Dies

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: Heaven make thee free of it! I follow thee.
\LINE: I am dead, Horatio. Wretched queen, adieu!
\LINE: You that look pale and tremble at this chance,
\LINE: That are but mutes or audience to this act,
\LINE: Had I but time--as this fell sergeant, death,
\LINE: Is strict in his arrest--O, I could tell you--
\LINE: But let it be. Horatio, I am dead;
\LINE: Thou livest; report me and my cause aright
\LINE: To the unsatisfied.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Never believe it:
\LINE: I am more an antique Roman than a Dane:
\LINE: Here's yet some liquor left.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: As thou'rt a man,
\LINE: Give me the cup: let go; by heaven, I'll have't.
\LINE: O good Horatio, what a wounded name,
\LINE: Things standing thus unknown, shall live behind me!
\LINE: If thou didst ever hold me in thy heart
\LINE: Absent thee from felicity awhile,
\LINE: And in this harsh world draw thy breath in pain,
\LINE: To tell my story.
\STAGEDIR: March afar off, and shot within
\LINE: What warlike noise is this?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: OSRIC
\LINE: Young Fortinbras, with conquest come from Poland,
\LINE: To the ambassadors of England gives
\LINE: This warlike volley.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HAMLET
\LINE: O, I die, Horatio;
\LINE: The potent poison quite o'er-crows my spirit:
\LINE: I cannot live to hear the news from England;
\LINE: But I do prophesy the election lights
\LINE: On Fortinbras: he has my dying voice;
\LINE: So tell him, with the occurrents, more and less,
\LINE: Which have solicited. The rest is silence.
>


\STAGEDIR: Dies

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Now cracks a noble heart. Good night sweet prince:
\LINE: And flights of angels sing thee to thy rest!
\LINE: Why does the drum come hither?
>

\STAGEDIR: March within
\STAGEDIR<Enter FORTINBRAS, the English Ambassadors,
and others>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: PRINCE FORTINBRAS
\LINE: Where is this sight?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: What is it ye would see?
\LINE: If aught of woe or wonder, cease your search.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: PRINCE FORTINBRAS
\LINE: This quarry cries on havoc. O proud death,
\LINE: What feast is toward in thine eternal cell,
\LINE: That thou so many princes at a shot
\LINE: So bloodily hast struck?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: First Ambassador
\LINE: The sight is dismal;
\LINE: And our affairs from England come too late:
\LINE: The ears are senseless that should give us hearing,
\LINE: To tell him his commandment is fulfill'd,
\LINE: That Rosencrantz and Guildenstern are dead:
\LINE: Where should we have our thanks?
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Not from his mouth,
\LINE: Had it the ability of life to thank you:
\LINE: He never gave commandment for their death.
\LINE: But since, so jump upon this bloody question,
\LINE: You from the Polack wars, and you from England,
\LINE: Are here arrived give order that these bodies
\LINE: High on a stage be placed to the view;
\LINE: And let me speak to the yet unknowing world
\LINE: How these things came about: so shall you hear
\LINE: Of carnal, bloody, and unnatural acts,
\LINE: Of accidental judgments, casual slaughters,
\LINE: Of deaths put on by cunning and forced cause,
\LINE: And, in this upshot, purposes mistook
\LINE: Fall'n on the inventors' reads: all this can I
\LINE: Truly deliver.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: PRINCE FORTINBRAS
\LINE: Let us haste to hear it,
\LINE: And call the noblest to the audience.
\LINE: For me, with sorrow I embrace my fortune:
\LINE: I have some rights of memory in this kingdom,
\LINE: Which now to claim my vantage doth invite me.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: HORATIO
\LINE: Of that I shall have also cause to speak,
\LINE: And from his mouth whose voice will draw on more;
\LINE: But let this same be presently perform'd,
\LINE: Even while men's minds are wild; lest more mischance
\LINE: On plots and errors, happen.
>

\SPEECH<
\SPEAKER: PRINCE FORTINBRAS
\LINE: Let four captains
\LINE: Bear Hamlet, like a soldier, to the stage;
\LINE: For he was likely, had he been put on,
\LINE: To have proved most royally: and, for his passage,
\LINE: The soldiers' music and the rites of war
\LINE: Speak loudly for him.
\LINE: Take up the bodies: such a sight as this
\LINE: Becomes the field, but here shows much amiss.
\LINE: Go, bid the soldiers shoot.
>


\STAGEDIR<A dead march. Exeunt, bearing off the dead
bodies; after which a peal of ordnance is shot off>
>
>
>
